Some Definitions
================

   The @{b}tar@{ub} program is used to create and manipulate @{b}tar@{ub} archives.  An
@{i}archive@{ui} is a single file which contains the contents of many files,
while still identifying the names of the files, their owner(s), and so
forth.  (In addition, archives record access permissions, user and
group, size in bytes, and last modification time.  Some archives also
record the file names in each archived directory, as well as other file
and directory information.)  You can use @{b}tar@{ub} to @{i}create@{ui} a new archive in
a specified directory.

   The files inside an archive are called @{i}members@{ui}.  Within this manual,
we use the term @{i}file@{ui} to refer only to files accessible in the normal
ways (by @{b}ls@{ub}, @{b}cat@{ub}, and so forth), and the term @{i}member@{ui} to refer only to
the members of an archive.  Similarly, a @{i}file name@{ui} is the name of a
file, as it resides in the filesystem, and a @{i}member name@{ui} is the name of
an archive member within the archive.

   The term @{i}extraction@{ui} refers to the process of copying an archive
member (or multiple members) into a file in the filesystem.  Extracting
all the members of an archive is often called @{i}extracting the archive@{ui}.
The term @{i}unpack@{ui} can also be used to refer to the extraction of many or
all the members of an archive.  Extracting an archive does not destroy
the archive's structure, just as creating an archive does not destroy
the copies of the files that exist outside of the archive.  You may
also @{i}list@{ui} the members in a given archive (this is often thought of as
"printing" them to the standard output, or the command line), or @{i}append@{ui}
members to a pre-existing archive.  All of these operations can be
peformed using @{b}tar@{ub}.


@endnode

