What @{b}tar@{ub} Does
=============

   The @{b}tar@{ub} program provides the ability to create @{b}tar@{ub} archives, as well
as various other kinds of manipulation.  For example, you can use @{b}tar@{ub}
on previously created archives to extract files, to store additional
files, or to update or list files which were already stored.

   Initially, @{b}tar@{ub} archives were used to store files conveniently on
magnetic tape.  The name @{b}tar@{ub} comes from this use; it stands for @{b}t@{ub}ape
@{b}ar@{ub}chiver.  Despite the utility's name, @{b}tar@{ub} can direct its output to
available devices, files, or other programs (using pipes).  @{b}tar@{ub} may
even access remote devices or files (as archives).

   You can use @{b}tar@{ub} archives in many ways.  We want to stress a few of
them: storage, backup, and transportation.

Storage
     Often, @{b}tar@{ub} archives are used to store related files for convenient
     file transfer over a network.  For example, the GNU Project
     distributes its software bundled into @{b}tar@{ub} archives, so that all
     the files relating to a particular program (or set of related
     programs) can be transferred as a single unit.

     A magnetic tape can store several files in sequence.  However, the
     tape has no names for these files; it only knows their relative
     position on the tape.  One way to store several files on one tape
     and retain their names is by creating a @{b}tar@{ub} archive.  Even when
     the basic transfer mechanism can keep track of names, as FTP can,
     the nuisance of handling multiple files, directories, and multiple
     links makes @{b}tar@{ub} archives useful.

     Archive files are also used for long-term storage.  You can think
     of this as transportation from the present into the future.  (It
     is a science-fiction idiom that you can move through time as well
     as in space; the idea here is that @{b}tar@{ub} can be used to move
     archives in all dimensions, even time!)

Backup
     Because the archive created by @{b}tar@{ub} is capable of preserving file
     information and directory structure, @{b}tar@{ub} is commonly used for
     performing full and incremental backups of disks.  A backup puts a
     collection of files (possibly pertaining to many users and
     projects) together on a disk or a tape.  This guards against
     accidental destruction of the information in those files.  GNU @{b}tar@{ub}
     has special features that allow it to be used to make incremental
     and full dumps of all the files in a filesystem.

Transportation
     You can create an archive on one system, transfer it to another
     system, and extract the contents there.  This allows you to
     transport a group of files from one system to another.


@endnode

