Basic @{b}tar@{ub} Operations and Options
================================

@{b}   tar@{ub} can take a wide variety of arguments which specify and define
the actions it will have on the particular set of files or the archive.
The main types of arguments to @{b}tar@{ub} fall into one of two classes:
operations, and options.

   Some arguments fall into a class called @{i}operations@{ui}; exactly one of
these is both allowed and required for any instance of using @{b}tar@{ub}; you
may @{i}not@{ui} specify more than one.  People sometimes speak of @{i}operating
modes@{ui}.  You are in a particular operating mode when you have specified
the operation which specifies it; there are eight operations in total,
and thus there are eight operating modes.

   The other arguments fall into the class known as @{i}options@{ui}.  You are
not required to specify any options, and you are allowed to specify more
than one at a time (depending on the way you are using @{b}tar@{ub} at that
time).  Some options are used so frequently, and are so useful for
helping you type commands more carefully that they are effectively
"required".  We will discuss them in this chapter.

   You can write most of the @{b}tar@{ub} operations and options in any of three
forms: long (mnemonic) form, short form, and old style.  Some of the
operations and options have no short or "old" forms; however, the
operations and options which we will cover in this tutorial have
corresponding abbreviations.   We will indicate those abbreviations
appropriately to get you used to seeing them.  (Note that the "old
style" option forms exist in GNU @{b}tar@{ub} for compatibility with Unix @{b}tar@{ub}.
We present a full discussion of this way of writing options and
operations appears in @{"Old Options" link "Old Options"}, and we discuss the other two styles
of writing options in @{"Mnemonic Options" link "Mnemonic Options"} and @{"Short Options" link "Short Options"}.)

   In the examples and in the text of this tutorial, we usually use the
long forms of operations and options; but the "short" forms produce the
same result and can make typing long @{b}tar@{ub} commands easier.  For example,
instead of typing

     tar --create --verbose --file=afiles.tar apple angst aspic

you can type
     tar -c -v -f afiles.tar apple angst aspic

or even
     tar -cvf afiles.tar apple angst aspic

For more information on option syntax, see @{"Advanced tar" link "Advanced tar"}.  In
discussions in the text, when we name an option by its long form, we
also give the corresponding short option in parentheses.

   The term, "option", can be confusing at times, since "operations"
are often lumped in with the actual, @{i}optional@{ui} "options" in certain
general class statements.  For example, we just talked about "short and
long forms of options and operations".  However, experienced @{b}tar@{ub} users
often refer to these by shorthand terms such as, "short and long
options".  This term assumes that the "operations" are included, also.
Context will help you determine which definition of "options" to use.

   Similarly, the term "command" can be confusing, as it is often used
in two different ways.  People sometimes refer to @{b}tar@{ub} "commands".  A
@{b}tar@{ub} @{i}command@{ui} is the entire command line of user input which tells @{b}tar@{ub}
what to do -- including the operation, options, and any arguments (file
names, pipes, other commands, etc).  However, you will also sometimes
hear the term "the @{b}tar@{ub} command".  When the word "command" is used
specifically like this, a person is usually referring to the @{b}tar@{ub}
@{i}operation@{ui}, not the whole line.  Again, use context to figure out which
of the meanings the speaker intends.


@endnode

@node "frequent operations" "tar.guide/frequent operations"
@next "Two Frequent Options"
@prev "basic tar options"
@toc "Tutorial"

The Three Most Frequently Used Operations
=========================================

   Here are the three most frequently used operations (both short and
long forms), as well as a brief description of their meanings.  The
rest of this chapter will cover how to use these operations in detail.
We will present the rest of the operations in the next chapter.

@{b}--create@{ub}
@{b}-c@{ub}
     Create a new @{b}tar@{ub} archive.

@{b}--list@{ub}
@{b}-t@{ub}
     List the contents of an archive.

@{b}--extract@{ub}
@{b}-x@{ub}
     Extract one or more members from an archive.


@endnode

@node "Two Frequent Options" "tar.guide/Two Frequent Options"
@next "create"
@prev "frequent operations"
@toc "Tutorial"

Two Frequently Used Options
===========================

   To understand how to run @{b}tar@{ub} in the three operating modes listed
previously, you also need to understand how to use two of the options to
@{b}tar@{ub}: @{b}--file@{ub} (which takes an archive file as an argument) and @{b}--verbose@{ub}.
(You are usually not @{i}required@{ui} to specify either of these options when
you run @{b}tar@{ub}, but they can be very useful in making things more clear
and helping you avoid errors.)


 @{" file tutorial " link "file tutorial"}  
 @{" verbose tutorial " link "verbose tutorial"}  
 @{" help tutorial " link "help tutorial"}


@endnode

@node "file tutorial" "tar.guide/file tutorial"
@next "verbose tutorial"
@prev "Two Frequent Options"
@toc "Two Frequent Options"

The @{b}--file@{ub} Option
-----------------

@{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}
@{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}
     Specify the name of an archive file.

   You can specify an argument for the @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f
ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) option whenever you use @{b}tar@{ub}; this option determines the
name of the archive file that @{b}tar@{ub} will work on.

   If you don't specify this argument, then @{b}tar@{ub} will use a default,
usually some physical tape drive attached to your machine.  If there is
no tape drive attached, or the default is not meaningful, then @{b}tar@{ub} will
print an error message.  The error message might look roughly like one
of the following:

     tar: can't open /dev/rmt8 : No such device or address
     tar: can't open /dev/rsmt0 : I/O error

To avoid confusion, we recommend that you always specfiy an archive file
name by using @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) when writing your
@{b}tar@{ub} commands.  For more information on using the @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}
(@{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) option, see @{"file" link "file"}.


@endnode

@node "verbose tutorial" "tar.guide/verbose tutorial"
@next "help tutorial"
@prev "file tutorial"
@toc "Two Frequent Options"

The @{b}--verbose@{ub} Option
--------------------

@{b}--verbose@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
     Show the files being worked on as @{b}tar@{ub} is running.

   @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) shows details about the results of running @{b}tar@{ub}.  This
can be especially useful when the results might not be obvious.  For
example, if you want to see the progress of @{b}tar@{ub} as it writes files into
the archive, you can use the @{b}--verbose@{ub} option.  In the beginning, you
may find it useful to use @{b}--verbose@{ub} at all times; when you are more
accustomed to @{b}tar@{ub}, you will likely want to use it at certain times but
not at others.  We will use @{b}--verbose@{ub} at times to help make something
clear, and we will give many examples both using and not using
@{b}--verbose@{ub} to show the differences.

   Sometimes, a single instance of @{b}--verbose@{ub} on the command line will
show a full, @{b}ls@{ub} style listing of an archive or files, giving sizes,
owners, and similar information.  Other times, @{b}--verbose@{ub} will only show
files or members that the particular operation is operating on at the
time.  In the latter case, you can use @{b}--verbose@{ub} twice in a command to
get a listing such as that in the former case.  For example, instead of
saying

     tar -cvf afiles.tar apple angst aspic

above, you might say

     tar -cvvf afiles.tar apple angst aspic

This works equally well using short or long forms of options.  Using
long forms, you would simply write out the mnemonic form of the option
twice, like this:

     $ tar --create --verbose --verbose ...

Note that you must double the hyphens properly each time.

   Later in the tutorial, we will give examples using
@{b}--verbose --verbose@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "help tutorial" "tar.guide/help tutorial"
@prev "verbose tutorial"
@toc "Two Frequent Options"

Getting Help: Using the @{b}--help@{ub} Option
-------------------------------------

@{b}--help@{ub}
     The @{b}--help@{ub} option to @{b}tar@{ub} prints out a very brief list of all
     operations and option available for the current version of @{b}tar@{ub}
     available on your system.


@endnode

@node "create" "tar.guide/create"
@next "list"
@prev "Two Frequent Options"
@toc "Tutorial"

How to Create Archives
======================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   One of the basic operations of @{b}tar@{ub} is @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}), which you use
to create a @{b}tar@{ub} archive.  We will explain @{b}--create@{ub} first because, in
order to learn about the other operations, you will find it useful to
have an archive available to practice on.

   To make this easier, in this section you will first create a
directory containing three files.  Then, we will show you how to create
an @{i}archive@{ui} (inside the new directory).  Both the directory, and the
archive are specifically for you to practice on.  The rest of this
chapter and the next chapter will show many examples using this
directory and the files you will create: some of those files may be
other directories and other archives.

   The three files you will archive in this example are called @{b}blues@{ub},
@{b}folk@{ub}, and @{b}jazz@{ub}.  The archive is called @{b}collection.tar@{ub}.

   This section will proceed slowly, detailing how to use @{b}--create@{ub} in
@{b}verbose@{ub} mode, and showing examples using both short and long forms.  In
the rest of the tutorial, and in the examples in the next chapter, we
will proceed at a slightly quicker pace.  This section moves more
slowly to allow beginning users to understand how @{b}tar@{ub} works.


 @{" prepare for examples " link "prepare for examples"}  
 @{" Creating the archive " link "Creating the archive"}  
 @{" create verbose     " link "create verbose"}  
 @{" short create       " link "short create"}  
 @{" create dir         " link "create dir"}


@endnode

@node "prepare for examples" "tar.guide/prepare for examples"
@next "Creating the archive"
@prev "create"
@toc "create"

Preparing a Practice Directory for Examples
-------------------------------------------

   To follow along with this and future examples, create a new directory
called @{b}practice@{ub} containing files called @{b}blues@{ub}, @{b}folk@{ub} and @{b}jazz@{ub}.  The
files can contain any information you like: ideally, they should
contain information which relates to their names, and be of different
lengths.  Our examples assume that @{b}practice@{ub} is a subdirectory of your
home directory.

   Now @{b}cd@{ub} to the directory named @{b}practice@{ub}; @{b}practice@{ub} is now your @{i}working
directory@{ui}.  (@{i}Please note@{ui}: Although the full path name of this directory
is @{b}/HOMEDIR/practice@{ub}, in our examples we will refer to this directory
as @{b}practice@{ub}; the HOMEDIR is presumed.

   In general, you should check that the files to be archived exist
where you think they do (in the working directory) by running @{b}ls@{ub}.
Because you just created the directory and the files and have changed to
that directory, you probably don't need to do that this time.

   It is very important to make sure there isn't already a file in the
working directory with the archive name you intend to use (in this case,
@{b}collection.tar@{ub}), or that you don't care about its contents.  Whenever
you use @{b}create@{ub}, @{b}tar@{ub} will erase the current contents of the file named
by @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) if it exists.  @{b}tar@{ub} will not
tell you if you are about to overwrite a file unless you specify an
option which does this .  To add files to an existing archive, you need
to use a different option, such as @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}); see @{"append" link "append"} for
information on how to do this.


@endnode

@node "Creating the archive" "tar.guide/Creating the archive"
@next "create verbose"
@prev "prepare for examples"
@toc "create"

Creating the Archive
--------------------

   To place the files @{b}blues@{ub}, @{b}folk@{ub}, and @{b}jazz@{ub} into an archive named
@{b}collection.tar@{ub}, use the following command:

     $ tar --create --file=collection.tar blues folk jazz

   The order of the arguments is not very important, @{i}when using long
option forms@{ui}.  You could also say:

     $ tar blues --create folk --file=collection.tar jazz

However, you can see that this order is harder to understand; this is
why we will list the arguments in the order that makes the commands
easiest to understand (and we encourage you to do the same when you use
@{b}tar@{ub}, to avoid errors).

   Note that the part of the command which says, @{b}--file=collection.tar@{ub}
is considered to be @{i}one@{ui} argument.  If you substituted any other string
of characters for @{b}`collection.tar'@{ub},  then that string would become the
name of the archive file you create.

   The order of the options becomes more important when you begin to use
short forms.  With short forms, if you type commands in the wrong order
(even if you type them correctly in all other ways), you may end up with
results you don't expect.  For this reason, it is a good idea to get
into the habit of typing options in the order that makes inherent sense.
See @{"short create" link "short create"} for more information on this.

   In this example, you type the command as shown above: @{b}--create@{ub} is
the operation which creates the new archive (@{b}collection.tar@{ub}), and
@{b}--file@{ub} is the option which lets you give it the name you chose.  The
files, @{b}blues@{ub}, @{b}folk@{ub}, and @{b}jazz@{ub}, are now members of the archive,
@{b}collection.tar@{ub} (they are @{i}file name arguments@{ui} to the @{b}--create@{ub} operation)
.  Now that they are are in the archive, they are called @{i}archive
members@{ui}, not files .

   When you create an archive, you @{i}must@{ui} specify which files you want
placed in the archive.  If you do not specify any archive members, GNU
@{b}tar@{ub} will complain.

   If you now list the contents of the working directory (@{b}ls@{ub}), you will
find the archive file listed as well as the files you saw previously:

     blues   folk   jazz   collection.tar

Creating the archive @{b}collection.tar@{ub} did not destroy the copies of the
files in the directory.

   Keep in mind that if you don't indicate an operation, @{b}tar@{ub} will not
run and will prompt you for one.  If you don't name any files, @{b}tar@{ub} will
complain.  You must have write access to the working directory, or else
you will not be able to create an archive in that directory.

@{i}   Caution@{ui}: Do not attempt to use @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) to add files to an
existing archive; it will delete the archive and write a new one.  Use
@{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}) instead.  See @{"append" link "append"}.


@endnode

@node "create verbose" "tar.guide/create verbose"
@next "short create"
@prev "Creating the archive"
@toc "create"

Running @{b}--create@{ub} with @{b}--verbose@{ub}
-------------------------------

   If you include the @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) option on the command line, @{b}tar@{ub}
will list the files it is acting on as it is working.  In verbose mode,
the @{b}create@{ub} example above would appear as:

     $ tar --create --verbose --file=collection.tar blues folk jazz
     blues
     folk
     jazz

   This example is just like the example we showed which did not use
@{b}--verbose@{ub}, except that @{b}tar@{ub} generated the remaining lines .

   In the rest of the examples in this chapter, we will frequently use
@{b}verbose@{ub} mode so we can show actions or @{b}tar@{ub} responses that you would
otherwise not see, and which are important for you to understand.


@endnode

@node "short create" "tar.guide/short create"
@next "create dir"
@prev "create verbose"
@toc "create"

Short Forms with @{b}create@{ub}
-----------------------

   As we said before, the @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) operation is one of the most
basic uses of @{b}tar@{ub}, and you will use it countless times.  Eventually,
you will probably want to use abbreviated (or "short") forms of
options.  A full discussion of the three different forms that options
can take appears in @{"Styles" link "Styles"}; for now, here is what the previous example
(including the @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) option) looks like using short option
forms:

     $ tar -cvf collection.tar blues folk jazz
     blues
     folk
     jazz

As you can see, the system responds the same no matter whether you use
long or short option forms.

   One difference between using short and long option forms is that,
although the exact placement of arguments following options is no more
specific when using short forms, it is easier to become confused and
make a mistake when using short forms.  For example, suppose you
attempted the above example in the following way:

     $ tar -cfv collection.tar blues folk jazz

In this case, @{b}tar@{ub} will make an archive file called @{b}v@{ub}, containing the
files @{b}blues@{ub}, @{b}folk@{ub}, and @{b}jazz@{ub}, because the @{b}v@{ub} is the closest "file name"
to the @{b}-f@{ub} option, and is thus taken to be the chosen archive file name.
@{b}tar@{ub} will try to add a file called @{b}collection.tar@{ub} to the @{b}v@{ub} archive file;
if the file @{b}collection.tar@{ub} did not already exist, @{b}tar@{ub} will report an
error indicating that this file does not exist.  If the file
@{b}collection.tar@{ub} does already exist (e.g., from a previous command you
may have run), then @{b}tar@{ub} will add this file to the archive.  Because the
@{b}-v@{ub} option did not get registered, @{b}tar@{ub} will not run under @{b}verbose@{ub} mode,
and will not report its progress.

   The end result is that you may be quite confused about what happened,
and possibly overwrite a file.  To illustrate this further, we will show
you how an example we showed previously would look using short forms.

   This example,

     $ tar blues --create folk --file=collection.tar jazz

is confusing as it is.  When shown using short forms, however, it
becomes much more so:

     $ tar blues -c folk -f collection.tar jazz

It would be very easy to put the wrong string of characters immediately
following the @{b}-f@{ub}, but doing that could sacrifice valuable data.

   For this reason, we recommend that you pay very careful attention to
the order of options and placement of file and archive names,
especially when using short option forms.  Not having the option name
written out mnemonically can affect how well you remember which option
does what, and therefore where different names have to be placed.
(Placing options in an unusual order can also cause @{b}tar@{ub} to report an
error if you have set the shell environment variable, @{b}POSIXLY_CORRECT@{ub};
see @{"posix compliance" link "posix compliance"} for more information on this.)


@endnode

@node "create dir" "tar.guide/create dir"
@prev "short create"
@toc "create"

Archiving Directories
---------------------

   You can archive a directory by specifying its directory name as a
file name argument to @{b}tar@{ub}.  The files in the directory will be archived
relative to the working directory, and the directory will be re-created
along with its contents when the archive is extracted.

   To archive a directory, first move to its superior directory.  If you
have followed the previous instructions in this tutorial, you should
type:

     $ cd ..
     $

This will put you into the directory which contains @{b}practice@{ub}, i.e. your
home directory.  Once in the superior directory, you can specify the
subdirectory, @{b}practice@{ub}, as a file name argument.  To store @{b}practice@{ub} in
the new archive file @{b}music.tar@{ub}, type:

     $ tar --create --verbose --file=music.tar practice

@{b}tar@{ub} should output:

     practice/
     practice/blues
     practice/folk
     practice/jazz
     practice/collection.tar

   Note that the archive thus created is not in the subdirectory
@{b}practice@{ub}, but rather in the current working directory--the directory
from which @{b}tar@{ub} was invoked.  Before trying to archive a directory from
its superior directory, you should make sure you have write access to
the superior directory itself, not only the directory you are trying
archive with @{b}tar@{ub}.  For example, you will probably not be able to store
your home directory in an archive by invoking @{b}tar@{ub} from the root
directory; See @{"absolute" link "absolute"}.  (Note also that @{b}collection.tar@{ub}, the original
archive file, has itself been archived.  @{b}tar@{ub} will accept any file as a
file to be archived, regardless of its content.  When @{b}music.tar@{ub} is
extracted, the archive file @{b}collection.tar@{ub} will be re-written into the
file system).

   If you give @{b}tar@{ub} a command such as

     $ tar --create --file=foo.tar .

@{b}tar@{ub} will report @{b}tar: foo.tar is the archive; not dumped@{ub}.  This happens
because @{b}tar@{ub} creates the archive @{b}foo.tar@{ub} in the current directory before
putting any files into it.  Then, when @{b}tar@{ub} attempts to add all the
files in the directory @{b}.@{ub} to the archive, it notices that the file
@{b}foo.tar@{ub} is the same as the archive, and skips it.  (It makes no sense
to put an archive into itself.)  GNU @{b}tar@{ub} will continue in this case,
and create the archive normally, except for the exclusion of that one
file.  (@{i}Please note:@{ui} Other versions of @{b}tar@{ub} are not so clever; they will
enter an infinite loop when this happens, so you should not depend on
this behavior unless you are certain you are running GNU @{b}tar@{ub}.  )


@endnode

@node "list" "tar.guide/list"
@next "extract"
@prev "create"
@toc "Tutorial"

How to List Archives
====================

   Frequently, you will find yourself wanting to determine exactly what
a particular archive contains.  You can use the @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}) operation
to get the member names as they currently appear in the archive, as well
as various attributes of the files at the time they were archived.  For
example, you can examine the archive @{b}collection.tar@{ub} that you created in
the last section with the command,

     $ tar --list --file=collection.tar

The output of @{b}tar@{ub} would then be:

     blues
     folk
     jazz

The archive @{b}bfiles.tar@{ub} would list as follows:

     ./birds
     baboon
     ./box

Be sure to use a @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) option just as
with @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) to specify the name of the archive.

   If you use the @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) option with @{b}--list@{ub}, then @{b}tar@{ub} will
print out a listing reminiscent of @{b}ls -l@{ub}, showing owner, file size, and
so forth.

   If you had used @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) mode, the example above would look
like:

     $ tar --list --verbose --file=collection.tar folk
     -rw-rw-rw- myself user 62 1990-05-23 10:55 folk

   You can specify one or more individual member names as arguments when
using @{b}list@{ub}.  In this case, @{b}tar@{ub} will only list the names of members you
identify.  For example, @{b}tar --list --file=afiles.tar apple@{ub} would only
print @{b}apple@{ub}.

   Because @{b}tar@{ub} preserves paths, file names must be specified as they
appear in the archive (ie., relative to the directory from which the
archive was created).  Therefore, it is essential when specifying
member names to @{b}tar@{ub} that you give the exact member names.  For example,
@{b}tar --list --file=bfiles birds@{ub} would produce an error message something
like @{b}tar: birds: Not found in archive@{ub}, because there is no member named
@{b}birds@{ub}, only one named @{b}./birds@{ub}.  While the names @{b}birds@{ub} and @{b}./birds@{ub} name
the same file, @{i}member@{ui} names are compared using a simplistic name
comparison, in which an exact match is necessary.  See @{"absolute" link "absolute"}.

   However, @{b}tar --list --file=collection.tar folk@{ub} would respond with
@{b}folk@{ub}, because @{b}folk@{ub} is in the archive file @{b}collection.tar@{ub}.  If you are
not sure of the exact file name, try listing all the files in the
archive and searching for the one you expect to find; remember that if
you use @{b}--list@{ub} with no file names as arguments, @{b}tar@{ub} will print the
names of all the members stored in the specified archive.


 @{" list dir " link "list dir"}


@endnode

@node "list dir" "tar.guide/list dir"
@prev "list"
@toc "list"

Listing the Contents of a Stored Directory
------------------------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   To get information about the contents of an archived directory, use
the directory name as a file name argument in conjunction with @{b}--list@{ub}
(@{b}-t@{ub}).  To find out file attributes, include the @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) option.

   For example, to find out about files in the directory @{b}practice@{ub}, in
the archive file @{b}music.tar@{ub}, type:

     $ tar --list --verbose --file=music.tar practice

@{b}   tar@{ub} responds:

     drwxrwxrwx myself user 0 1990-05-31 21:49 practice/
     -rw-rw-rw- myself user 42 1990-05-21 13:29 practice/blues
     -rw-rw-rw- myself user 62 1990-05-23 10:55 practice/folk
     -rw-rw-rw- myself user 40 1990-05-21 13:30 practice/jazz
     -rw-rw-rw- myself user 10240 1990-05-31 21:49 practice/collection.tar

   When you use a directory name as a file name argument, @{b}tar@{ub} acts on
all the files (including sub-directories) in that directory.


@endnode

@node "extract" "tar.guide/extract"
@next "going further"
@prev "list"
@toc "Tutorial"

How to Extract Members from an Archive
======================================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   Creating an archive is only half the job--there is no point in
storing files in an archive if you can't retrieve them.  The act of
retrieving members from an archive so they can be used and manipulated
as unarchived files again is called @{i}extraction@{ui}.  To extract files from
an archive, use the @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}) operation.  As with @{b}--create@{ub}
(@{b}-c@{ub}), specify the name of the archive with @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f
ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}).  Extracting an archive does not modify the archive in
any way; you can extract it multiple times if you want or need to.

   Using @{b}--extract@{ub}, you can extract an entire archive, or specific
files.  The files can be directories containing other files, or not.  As
with @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) and @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}), you may use the short or the long
form of the operation without affecting the performance.


 @{" extracting archives " link "extracting archives"}  
 @{" extracting files  " link "extracting files"}  
 @{" extract dir       " link "extract dir"}  
 @{" failing commands  " link "failing commands"}


@endnode

@node "extracting archives" "tar.guide/extracting archives"
@next "extracting files"
@prev "extract"
@toc "extract"

Extracting an Entire Archive
----------------------------

   To extract an entire archive, specify the archive file name only,
with no individual file names as arguments.  For example,

     $ tar -xvf collection.tar

produces this:

     -rw-rw-rw- me user     28 1996-10-18 16:31 jazz
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     21 1996-09-23 16:44 blues
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     20 1996-09-23 16:44 folk


@endnode

@node "extracting files" "tar.guide/extracting files"
@next "extract dir"
@prev "extracting archives"
@toc "extract"

Extracting Specific Files
-------------------------

   To extract specific archive members, give their exact member names as
arguments, as printed by @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}).  If you had mistakenly deleted
one of the files you had placed in the archive @{b}collection.tar@{ub} earlier
(say, @{b}blues@{ub}), you can extract it from the archive without changing the
archive's structure.  It will be identical to the original file @{b}blues@{ub}
that you deleted.

   First, make sure you are in the @{b}practice@{ub} directory, and list the
files in the directory.  Now, delete the file, @{b}blues@{ub}, and list the
files in the directory again.

   You can now extract the member @{b}blues@{ub} from the archive file
@{b}collection.tar@{ub} like this:

     $ tar --extract --file=collection.tar blues

If you list the files in the directory again, you will see that the file
@{b}blues@{ub} has been restored, with its original permissions, creation times,
and owner.   (These parameters will be identical to those which the
file had when you originally placed it in the archive; any changes you
may have made before deleting the file from the file system, however,
will @{i}not@{ui} have been made to the archive member.)  The archive file,
@{b}collection.tar@{ub}, is the same as it was before you extracted @{b}blues@{ub}.  You
can confirm this by running @{b}tar@{ub} with @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}).

   Remember that as with other operations, specifying the exact member
name is important.  @{b}tar --extract --file=bfiles.tar birds@{ub} will fail,
because there is no member named @{b}birds@{ub}.  To extract the member named
@{b}./birds@{ub}, you must specify @{b}tar --extract --file=bfiles.tar ./birds@{ub}.  To
find the exact member names of the members of an archive, use @{b}--list@{ub}
(@{b}-t@{ub}) (see @{"list" link "list"}).

   If you give the @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) option, then @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub})
will print the names of the archive members as it extracts them.


@endnode

@node "extract dir" "tar.guide/extract dir"
@next "failing commands"
@prev "extracting files"
@toc "extract"

Extracting Files that are Directories
-------------------------------------

   Extracting directories which are members of an archive is similar to
extracting other files.  The main difference to be aware of is that if
the extracted directory has the same name as any directory already in
the working directory, then files in the extracted directory will be
placed into the directory of the same name.  Likewise, if there are
files in the pre-existing directory with the same names as the members
which you extract, the files from the extracted archive will overwrite
the files already in the working directory (and possible
subdirectories).  This will happen regardless of whether or not the
files in the working directory were more recent than those extracted.

   However, if a file was stored with a directory name as part of its
file name, and that directory does not exist under the working
directory when the file is extracted, @{b}tar@{ub} will create the directory.

   We can demonstrate how to use @{b}--extract@{ub} to extract a directory file
with an example.  Change to the @{b}practice@{ub} directory if you weren't
there, and remove the files @{b}folk@{ub} and @{b}jazz@{ub}.  Then, go back to the parent
directory and extract the archive @{b}music.tar@{ub}.  You may either extract
the entire archive, or you may extract only the files you just deleted.
To extract the entire archive, don't give any file names as arguments
after the archive name @{b}music.tar@{ub}.  To extract only the files you
deleted, use the following command:

     $ tar -xvf music.tar practice/folk practice/jazz

Because you created the directory with @{b}practice@{ub} as part of the file
names of each of the files by archiving the @{b}practice@{ub} directory as
@{b}practice@{ub}, you must give @{b}practice@{ub} as part of the file names when you
extract those files from the archive.


@endnode

@node "failing commands" "tar.guide/failing commands"
@prev "extract dir"
@toc "extract"

Commands That Will Fail
-----------------------

   Here are some sample commands you might try which will not work, and
why they won't work.

   If you try to use this command,

     $ tar -xvf music.tar folk jazz

you will get the following response:

     tar: folk: Not found in archive
     tar: jazz: Not found in archive
     $

This is because these files were not originally @{i}in@{ui} the parent directory
@{b}..@{ub}, where the archive is located; they were in the @{b}practice@{ub} directory,
and their file names reflect this:

     $ tar -tvf music.tar
     practice/folk
     practice/jazz
     practice/rock

Likewise, if you try to use this command,

     $ tar -tvf music.tar folk jazz

you would get a similar response.  Members with those names are not in
the archive.  You must use the correct member names in order to extract
the files from the archive.

   If you have forgotten the correct names of the files in the archive,
use @{b}tar --list --verbose@{ub} to list them correctly.


@endnode

