Invoking GNU @{b}tar@{ub}
****************

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   This chapter is about how one invokes the GNU @{b}tar@{ub} command, from the
command synopsis (see @{"Synopsis" link "Synopsis"}).  There are numerous options, and many
styles for writing them.  One mandatory option specifies the operation
@{b}tar@{ub} should perform (see @{"Operation Summary" link "Operation Summary"}), other options are meant to
detail how this operation should be performed (see @{"Option Summary" link "Option Summary"}).
Non-option arguments are not always interpreted the same way, depending
on what the operation is.

   You will find in this chapter everything about option styles and
rules for writing them (see @{"Styles" link "Styles"}).  On the other hand, operations
and options are fully described elsewhere, in other chapters.  Here,
you will find only synthetic descriptions for operations and options,
together with pointers to other parts of the @{b}tar@{ub} manual.

   Some options are so special they are fully described right in this
chapter.  They have the effect of inhibiting the normal operation of
@{b}tar@{ub} or else, they globally alter the amount of feedback the user
receives about what is going on.  These are the @{b}--help@{ub} and @{b}--version@{ub}
(see @{"help" link "help"}), @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) (see @{"verbose" link "verbose"}) and @{b}--interactive@{ub} (@{b}-w@{ub})
options (see @{"interactive" link "interactive"}).


