General Synopsis of @{b}tar@{ub}
=======================

   The GNU @{b}tar@{ub} program is invoked as either one of:

     tar OPTION... [NAME]...
     tar LETTER... [ARGUMENT]... [OPTION]... [NAME]...

   The second form is for when old options are being used.

   You can use @{b}tar@{ub} to store files in an archive, to extract them from
an archive, and to do other types of archive manipulation.  The primary
argument to @{b}tar@{ub}, which is called the @{i}operation@{ui}, specifies which action
to take.  The other arguments to @{b}tar@{ub} are either @{i}options@{ui}, which change
the way @{b}tar@{ub} performs an operation, or file names or archive members,
which specify the files or members @{b}tar@{ub} is to act on.

   You can actually type in arguments in any order, even if in this
manual the options always precede the other arguments, to make examples
easier to understand.  Further, the option stating the main operation
mode (the @{b}tar@{ub} main command) is usually given first.

   Each NAME in the synopsis above is interpreted as an archive member
name when the main command is one of @{b}--compare@{ub} (@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}), @{b}--delete@{ub},
@{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}), @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}) or @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}).  When naming
archive members, you must give the exact name of the member in the
archive, as it is printed by @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}).  For @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}) and
@{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}), these NAME arguments specify the names of either files
or directory hierarchies to place in the archive.  These files or
hierarchies should already exist in the file system, prior to the
execution of the @{b}tar@{ub} command.

@{b}   tar@{ub} interprets relative file names as being relative to the working
directory.  @{b}tar@{ub} will make all file names relative (by removing leading
slashes when archiving or restoring files), unless you specify
otherwise (using the @{b}--absolute-names@{ub} (@{b}-P@{ub}) option).  See @{"absolute" link "absolute"}, for
more information about @{b}--absolute-names@{ub} (@{b}-P@{ub}).

   If you give the name of a directory as either a file name or a member
name, then @{b}tar@{ub} acts recursively on all the files and directories
beneath that directory.  For example, the name @{b}/@{ub} identifies all the
files in the filesystem to @{b}tar@{ub}.

   The distinction between file names and archive member names is
especially important when shell globbing is used, and sometimes a
source of confusion for newcomers.  See @{"Wildcards" link "Wildcards"}, for more
information about globbing.  The problem is that shells may only glob
using existing files in the file system.  Only @{b}tar@{ub} itself may glob on
archive members, so when needed, you must ensure that wildcard
characters reach @{b}tar@{ub} without being interpreted by the shell first.
Using a backslash before @{b}*@{ub} or @{b}?@{ub}, or putting the whole argument between
quotes, is usually sufficient for this.

   Even if NAMEs are often specified on the command line, they can also
be read from a text file in the file system, using the
@{b}--files-from=FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub} (@{b}-T FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub}) option.

   If you don't use any file name arguments, @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}), @{b}--delete@{ub}
and @{b}--concatenate@{ub} (@{b}--catenate@{ub}, @{b}-A@{ub}) will do nothing, while @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub})
will usually yield a diagnostic and inhibit @{b}tar@{ub} execution.  The other
operations of @{b}tar@{ub} (@{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}), @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}), @{b}--compare@{ub}
(@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}), and @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub})) will act on the entire contents of the
archive.

   Besides successful exits, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} may fail for many reasons.  Some
reasons correspond to bad usage, that is, when the @{b}tar@{ub} command is
improperly written.  Errors may be encountered later, while
encountering an error processing the archive or the files.  Some errors
are recoverable, in which case the failure is delayed until @{b}tar@{ub} has
completed all its work.  Some errors are such that it would not
meaningful, or at least risky, to continue processing: @{b}tar@{ub} then aborts
processing immediately.  All abnormal exits, whether immediate or
delayed, should always be clearly diagnosed on @{b}stderr@{ub}, after a line
stating the nature of the error.

   GNU @{b}tar@{ub} returns only a few exit statuses.  I'm really aiming
simplicity in that area, for now.  If you are not using the @{b}--compare@{ub}
(@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}) option, zero means that everything went well, besides
maybe innocuous warnings.  Nonzero means that something went wrong.
Right now, as of today, "nonzero" is almost always 2, except for remote
operations, where it may be 128.


@endnode

@node "using tar options" "tar.guide/using tar options"
@next "Styles"
@prev "Synopsis"
@toc "tar invocation"

Using @{b}tar@{ub} Options
=================

   GNU @{b}tar@{ub} has a total of eight operating modes which allow you to
perform a variety of tasks.  You are required to choose one operating
mode each time you employ the @{b}tar@{ub} program by specifying one, and only
one operation as an argument to the @{b}tar@{ub} command (two lists of four
operations each may be found at @{"frequent operations" link "frequent operations"} and @{"Operations" link "Operations"}).
Depending on circumstances, you may also wish to customize how the
chosen operating mode behaves.  For example, you may wish to change the
way the output looks, or the format of the files that you wish to
archive may require you to do something special in order to make the
archive look right.

   You can customize and control @{b}tar@{ub}'s performance by running @{b}tar@{ub} with
one or more options (such as @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}), which we used in the
tutorial).  As we said in the tutorial, @{i}options@{ui} are arguments to @{b}tar@{ub}
which are (as their name suggests) optional.  Depending on the
operating mode, you may specify one or more options.  Different options
will have different effects, but in general they all change details of
the operation, such as archive format, archive name, or level of user
interaction.  Some options make sense with all operating modes, while
others are meaningful only with particular modes.  You will likely use
some options frequently, while you will only use others infrequently,
or not at all.  (A full list of options is available in see
@{"All Options" link "All Options"}.)

   Note that @{b}tar@{ub} options are case sensitive.  For example, the options
@{b}-T@{ub} and @{b}-t@{ub} are different; the first requires an argument for stating the
name of a file providing a list of NAMEs, while the second does not
require an argument and is another way to write @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}).

   In addition to the eight operations, there are many options to @{b}tar@{ub},
and three different styles for writing both: long (mnemonic) form,
short form, and old style.  These styles are discussed below.  Both the
options and the operations can be written in any of these three styles.


@endnode

@node "Styles" "tar.guide/Styles"
@next "All Options"
@prev "using tar options"
@toc "tar invocation"

The Three Option Styles
=======================

   There are three styles for writing operations and options to the
command line invoking @{b}tar@{ub}.  The different styles were developed at
different times during the history of @{b}tar@{ub}.  These styles will be
presented below, from the most recent to the oldest.

   Some options must take an argument.  (For example,
@{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) takes the name of an archive file
as an argument.  If you do not supply an archive file name, @{b}tar@{ub} will
use a default, but this can be confusing; thus, we recommend that you
always supply a specific archive file name.)  Where you @{i}place@{ui} the
arguments generally depends on which style of options you choose.  We
will detail specific information relevant to each option style in the
sections on the different option styles, below.  The differences are
subtle, yet can often be very important; incorrect option placement can
cause you to overwrite a number of important files.  We urge you to
note these differences, and only use the option style(s) which makes
the most sense to you until you feel comfortable with the others.


 @{" Mnemonic Options           " link "Mnemonic Options"}  Mnemonic Option Style
 @{" Short Options              " link "Short Options"}  Short Option Style
 @{" Old Options                " link "Old Options"}  Old Option Style
 @{" Mixing                     " link "Mixing"}  Mixing Option Styles


@endnode

@node "Mnemonic Options" "tar.guide/Mnemonic Options"
@next "Short Options"
@prev "Styles"
@toc "Styles"

Mnemonic Option Style
---------------------

   Each option has at least one long (or mnemonic) name starting with
two dashes in a row, e.g. @{b}list@{ub}.  The long names are more clear than
their corresponding short or old names.  It sometimes happens that a
single mnemonic option has many different different names which are
synonymous, such as @{b}--compare@{ub} and @{b}--diff@{ub}.  In addition, long option
names can be given unique abbreviations.  For example, @{b}--cre@{ub} can be
used in place of @{b}--create@{ub} because there is no other mnemonic option
which begins with @{b}cre@{ub}.  (One way to find this out is by trying it and
seeing what happens; if a particular abbreviation could represent more
than one option, @{b}tar@{ub} will tell you that that abbreviation is ambiguous
and you'll know that that abbreviation won't work.  You may also choose
to run @{b}tar --help@{ub} to see a list of options.  Be aware that if you run
@{b}tar@{ub} with a unique abbreviation for the long name of an option you
didn't want to use, you are stuck; @{b}tar@{ub} will perform the command as
ordered.)

   Mnemonic options are meant to be obvious and easy to remember, and
their meanings are generally easier to discern than those of their
corresponding short options (see below).  For example:

     $ tar --create --verbose --blocking-factor=20 --file=/dev/rmt0

gives a fairly good set of hints about what the command does, even for
those not fully acquainted with @{b}tar@{ub}.

   Mnemonic options which require arguments take those arguments
immediately following the option name; they are introduced by an equal
sign.  For example, the @{b}--file@{ub} option (which tells the name of the @{b}tar@{ub}
archive) is given a file such as @{b}archive.tar@{ub} as argument by using the
notation @{b}--file=archive.tar@{ub} for the mnemonic option.


@endnode

@node "Short Options" "tar.guide/Short Options"
@next "Old Options"
@prev "Mnemonic Options"
@toc "Styles"

Short Option Style
------------------

   Most options also have a short option name.  Short options start with
a single dash, and are followed by a single character, e.g. @{b}-t@{ub} (which
is equivalent to @{b}--list@{ub}).  The forms are absolutely identical in
function; they are interchangeable.

   The short option names are faster to type than long option names.

   Short options which require arguments take their arguments
immediately following the option, usually separated by white space.  It
is also possible to stick the argument right after the short option
name, using no intervening space.  For example, you might write
@{b}-f archive.tar@{ub} or @{b}-farchive.tar@{ub} instead of using @{b}--file=archive.tar@{ub}.
Both @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} and @{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} denote the option which
indicates a specific archive, here named @{b}archive.tar@{ub}.

   Short options' letters may be clumped together, but you are not
required to do this (as compared to old options; see below).  When short
options are clumped as a set, use one (single) dash for them all, e.g.
@{b}@{b}tar@{ub} -cvf@{ub}.  Only the last option in such a set is allowed to have an
argument(1).

   When the options are separated, the argument for each option which
requires an argument directly follows that option, as is usual for Unix
programs.  For example:

     $ tar -c -v -b 20 -f /dev/rmt0

   If you reorder short options' locations, be sure to move any
arguments that belong to them.  If you do not move the arguments
properly, you may end up overwriting files.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) Clustering many options, the last of which has an argument, is a
rather opaque way to write options.  Some wonder if GNU @{b}getopt@{ub} should
not even be made helpful enough for considering such usages as invalid.


@endnode

@node "Old Options" "tar.guide/Old Options"
@next "Mixing"
@prev "Short Options"
@toc "Styles"

Old Option Style
----------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   Like short options, old options are single letters.  However, old
options must be written together as a single clumped set, without
spaces separating them or dashes preceding them(1).  This set of
letters must be the first to appear on the command line, after the @{b}tar@{ub}
program name and some whitespace; old options cannot appear anywhere
else.  The letter of an old option is exactly the same letter as the
corresponding short option.  For example, the old option @{b}t@{ub} is the same
as the short option @{b}-t@{ub}, and consequently, the same as the mnemonic
option @{b}--list@{ub}.  So for example, the command @{b}tar cv@{ub} specifies the option
@{b}-v@{ub} in addition to the operation @{b}-c@{ub}.

   When options that need arguments are given together with the command,
all the associated arguments follow, in the same order as the options.
Thus, the example given previously could also be written in the old
style as follows:

     $ tar cvbf 20 /dev/rmt0

Here, @{b}20@{ub} is the argument of @{b}-b@{ub} and @{b}/dev/rmt0@{ub} is the argument of @{b}-f@{ub}.

   On the other hand, this old style syntax makes it difficult to match
option letters with their corresponding arguments, and is often
confusing.  In the command @{b}tar cvbf 20 /dev/rmt0@{ub}, for example, @{b}20@{ub} is
the argument for @{b}-b@{ub}, @{b}/dev/rmt0@{ub} is the argument for @{b}-f@{ub}, and @{b}-v@{ub} does not
have a corresponding argument.  Even using short options like in
@{b}tar -c -v -b 20 -f /dev/rmt0@{ub} is clearer, putting all arguments next to
the option they pertain to.

   If you want to reorder the letters in the old option argument, be
sure to reorder any corresponding argument appropriately.

   This old way of writing @{b}tar@{ub} options can surprise even experienced
users.  For example, the two commands:

     tar cfz archive.tar.gz file
     tar -cfz archive.tar.gz file

are quite different.  The first example uses @{b}archive.tar.gz@{ub} as the
value for option @{b}f@{ub} and recognizes the option @{b}z@{ub}.  The second example,
however, uses @{b}z@{ub} as the value for option @{b}f@{ub}--probably not what was
intended.

   Old options are kept for compatibility with old versions of @{b}tar@{ub}.

   This second example could be corrected in many ways, among which the
following are equivalent:

     tar -czf archive.tar.gz file
     tar -cf archive.tar.gz -z file
     tar cf archive.tar.gz -z file

   As far as we know, all @{b}tar@{ub} programs, GNU and non-GNU, support old
options.  GNU @{b}tar@{ub} supports them not only for historical reasons, but
also because many people are used to them.  For compatibility with Unix
@{b}tar@{ub}, the first argument is always treated as containing command and
option letters even if it doesn't start with @{b}-@{ub}.  Thus, @{b}tar c@{ub} is
equivalent to @{b}tar -c@{ub}: both of them specify the @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) command to
create an archive.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) Beware that if you precede options with a dash, you are
announcing the short option style instead of the old option style;
short options are decoded differently.


@endnode

@node "Mixing" "tar.guide/Mixing"
@prev "Old Options"
@toc "Styles"

Mixing Option Styles
--------------------

   All three styles may be intermixed in a single @{b}tar@{ub} command, so long
as the rules for each style are fully respected(1).  Old style options
and either of the modern styles of options may be mixed within a single
@{b}tar@{ub} command.  However, old style options must be introduced as the
first arguments only, following the rule for old options (old options
must appear directly after the @{b}tar@{ub} command and some whitespace).
Modern options may be given only after all arguments to the old options
have been collected.  If this rule is not respected, a modern option
might be falsely interpreted as the value of the argument to one of the
old style options.

   For example, all the following commands are wholly equivalent, and
illustrate the many combinations and orderings of option styles.

     tar --create --file=archive.tar
     tar --create -f archive.tar
     tar --create -farchive.tar
     tar --file=archive.tar --create
     tar --file=archive.tar -c
     tar -c --file=archive.tar
     tar -c -f archive.tar
     tar -c -farchive.tar
     tar -cf archive.tar
     tar -cfarchive.tar
     tar -f archive.tar --create
     tar -f archive.tar -c
     tar -farchive.tar --create
     tar -farchive.tar -c
     tar c --file=archive.tar
     tar c -f archive.tar
     tar c -farchive.tar
     tar cf archive.tar
     tar f archive.tar --create
     tar f archive.tar -c
     tar fc archive.tar

   On the other hand, the following commands are @{i}not@{ui} equivalent to the
previous set:

     tar -f -c archive.tar
     tar -fc archive.tar
     tar -fcarchive.tar
     tar -farchive.tarc
     tar cfarchive.tar

These last examples mean something completely different from what the
user intended (judging based on the example in the previous set which
uses long options, whose intent is therefore very clear).  The first
four specify that the @{b}tar@{ub} archive would be a file named @{b}-c@{ub}, @{b}c@{ub},
@{b}carchive.tar@{ub} or @{b}archive.tarc@{ub}, respectively.  The first two examples
also specify a single non-option, NAME argument having the value
@{b}archive.tar@{ub}.  The last example contains only old style option letters
(repeating option @{b}c@{ub} twice), not all of which are meaningful (eg., @{b}.@{ub}, @{b}h@{ub},
or @{b}i@{ub}), with no argument value.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) Before GNU @{b}tar@{ub} version 1.11.6, a bug prevented intermixing old
style options with mnemonic options in some cases.


@endnode

