Operations
----------

@{b}--append@{ub}
@{b}-r@{ub}
     Appends files to the end of the archive.  See @{"append" link "append"}.

@{b}--catenate@{ub}
@{b}-A@{ub}
     Same as @{b}--concatenate@{ub}.  See @{"concatenate" link "concatenate"}.

@{b}--compare@{ub}
@{b}-d@{ub}
     Compares archive members with their counterparts in the file
     system, and reports differences in file size, mode, owner,
     modification date and contents.  See @{"compare" link "compare"}.

@{b}--concatenate@{ub}
@{b}-A@{ub}
     Appends other @{b}tar@{ub} archives to the end of the archive.  See
     @{"concatenate" link "concatenate"}.

@{b}--create@{ub}
@{b}-c@{ub}
     Creates a new @{b}tar@{ub} archive.  See @{"create" link "create"}.

@{b}--delete@{ub}
     Deletes members from the archive.  Don't try this on a archive on a
     tape!  See @{"delete" link "delete"}.

@{b}--diff@{ub}
@{b}-d@{ub}
     Same @{b}--compare@{ub}.  See @{"compare" link "compare"}.

@{b}--extract@{ub}
@{b}-x@{ub}
     Extracts members from the archive into the file system.  See
     @{"extract" link "extract"}.

@{b}--get@{ub}
@{b}-x@{ub}
     Same as @{b}--extract@{ub}.   See @{"extract" link "extract"}.

@{b}--list@{ub}
@{b}-t@{ub}
     Lists the members in an archive.  See @{"list" link "list"}.

@{b}--update@{ub}
@{b}-u@{ub}
     Adds files to the end of the archive, but only if they are newer
     than their counterparts already in the archive, or if they do not
     already exist in the archive.  See @{"update" link "update"}.


@endnode

@node "Option Summary" "tar.guide/Option Summary"
@next "Short Option Summary"
@prev "Operation Summary"
@toc "All Options"

@{b}tar@{ub} Options
-----------

@{b}--absolute-names@{ub}
@{b}-P@{ub}
     Normally when creating an archive, @{b}tar@{ub} strips an initial @{b}/@{ub} from
     member names.  This option disables that behavior.  .

@{b}--after-date@{ub}
     (See @{b}--newer@{ub}; .)

@{b}--atime-preserve@{ub}
     Tells @{b}tar@{ub} to preserve the access time field in a file's inode when
     dumping it.  .

@{b}--backup=BACKUP-TYPE@{ub}
     Rather than deleting files from the file system, @{b}tar@{ub} will back
     them up using simple or numbered backups, depending upon
     BACKUP-TYPE.  .

@{b}--block-number@{ub}
@{b}-R@{ub}
     With this option present, @{b}tar@{ub} prints error messages for read errors
     with the block number in the archive file.  .

@{b}--blocking-factor=BLOCKING@{ub}
@{b}-b BLOCKING@{ub}
     Sets the blocking factor @{b}tar@{ub} uses to BLOCKING x 512 bytes per
     record.  .

@{b}--checkpoint@{ub}
     This option directs @{b}tar@{ub} to print periodic checkpoint messages as it
     reads through the archive.  Its intended for when you want a visual
     indication that @{b}tar@{ub} is still running, but don't want to see
     @{b}--verbose@{ub} output.  .

@{b}--compress@{ub}
@{b}--uncompress@{ub}
@{b}-Z@{ub}
@{b}     tar@{ub} will use the @{b}compress@{ub} program when reading or writing the
     archive.  This allows you to directly act on archives while saving
     space.  .

@{b}--confirmation@{ub}
     (See @{b}--interactive@{ub};  .)

@{b}--dereference@{ub}
@{b}-h@{ub}
     When creating a @{b}tar@{ub} archive, @{b}tar@{ub} will archive the file that a
     symbolic link points to, rather than archiving the symlink.  .

@{b}--directory=DIR@{ub}
@{b}-C DIR@{ub}
     When this option is specified, @{b}tar@{ub} will change its current
     directory to DIR before performing any operations.  When this
     option is used during archive creation, it is order sensitive.  .

@{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub}
     When performing operations, @{b}tar@{ub} will skip files that match
     PATTERN.  .

@{b}--exclude-from=FILE@{ub}
@{b}-X FILE@{ub}
     Similar to @{b}--exclude@{ub}, except @{b}tar@{ub} will use the list of patterns in
     the file FILE.  .

@{b}--file=ARCHIVE@{ub}
@{b}-f ARCHIVE@{ub}
@{b}     tar@{ub} will use the file ARCHIVE as the @{b}tar@{ub} archive it performs
     operations on, rather than @{b}tar@{ub}'s compilation dependent default.  .

@{b}--files-from=FILE@{ub}
@{b}-T FILE@{ub}
@{b}     tar@{ub} will use the contents of FILE as a list of archive members or
     files to operate on, in addition to those specified on the
     command-line.  .

@{b}--force-local@{ub}
     Forces @{b}tar@{ub} to interpret the filename given to @{b}--file@{ub} as a local
     file, even if it looks like a remote tape drive name.  .

@{b}--group=GROUP@{ub}
     Files added to the @{b}tar@{ub} archive will have a group id of GROUP,
     rather than the group from the source file.  GROUP is first decoded
     as a group symbolic name, but if this interpretation fails, it has
     to be a decimal numeric group ID.  .

     Also see the comments for the @{b}--owner=USER@{ub} option.

@{b}--gunzip@{ub}
     (See @{b}--gzip@{ub}; .)

@{b}--gzip@{ub}
@{b}--gunzip@{ub}
@{b}--ungzip@{ub}
@{b}-z@{ub}
     This option tells @{b}tar@{ub} to read or write archives through @{b}gzip@{ub},
     allowing @{b}tar@{ub} to directly operate on several kinds of compressed
     archives transparently.  .

@{b}--help@{ub}
@{b}     tar@{ub} will print out a short message summarizing the operations and
     options to @{b}tar@{ub} and exit.  .

@{b}--ignore-failed-read@{ub}
     Instructs @{b}tar@{ub} to exit successfully if it encounters an unreadable
     file.  See @{"Reading" link "Reading"}.

@{b}--ignore-umask@{ub}
     (See @{b}--preserve-permissions@{ub}; see @{"Writing" link "Writing"}.)

@{b}--ignore-zeros@{ub}
@{b}-i@{ub}
     With this option, @{b}tar@{ub} will ignore zeroed blocks in the archive,
     which normally signals EOF.  See @{"Reading" link "Reading"}.

@{b}--incremental@{ub}
@{b}-G@{ub}
     Used to inform @{b}tar@{ub} that it is working with an  old GNU-format
     incremental backup archive.  It is intended primarily for backwards
     compatibility only.  .

@{b}--info-script=SCRIPT-FILE@{ub}
@{b}--new-volume-script=SCRIPT-FILE@{ub}
@{b}-F SCRIPT-FILE@{ub}
     When @{b}tar@{ub} is performing multi-tape backups, SCRIPT-FILE is run at
     the end of each tape.  .

@{b}--interactive@{ub}
@{b}--confirmation@{ub}
@{b}-w@{ub}
     Specifies that @{b}tar@{ub} should ask the user for confirmation before
     performing potentially destructive options, such as overwriting
     files.  .

@{b}--keep-old-files@{ub}
@{b}-k@{ub}
     When extracting files from an archive, @{b}tar@{ub} will not overwrite
     existing files if this option is present.  See @{"Writing" link "Writing"}.

@{b}--label=NAME@{ub}
@{b}-V NAME@{ub}
     When creating an archive, instructs @{b}tar@{ub} to write NAME as a name
     record in the archive.  When extracting or listing archives, @{b}tar@{ub}
     will only operate on archives that have a label matching the
     pattern specified in NAME.  .

@{b}--listed-incremental=SNAPSHOT-FILE@{ub}
@{b}-g SNAPSHOT-FILE@{ub}
     During a @{b}--create@{ub} operation, specifies that the archive that @{b}tar@{ub}
     creates is a new GNU-format incremental backup, using
     SNAPSHOT-FILE to determine which files to backup.  With other
     operations, informs @{b}tar@{ub} that the archive is in incremental format.
     .

@{b}--mode=PERMISSIONS@{ub}
     When adding files to an archive, @{b}tar@{ub} will use PERMISSIONS for the
     archive members, rather than the permissions from the files.  The
     program @{b}chmod@{ub} and this @{b}tar@{ub} option share the same syntax for what
     PERMISSIONS might be.  See @{"Permissions" link "filetutils.guide/File permissions"}.  This reference also has
     useful information for those not being overly familiar with the
     Unix permission system.

     Of course, PERMISSIONS might be plainly specified as an octal
     number.  However, by using generic symbolic modifications to mode
     bits, this allows more flexibility.  For example, the value @{b}a+rw@{ub}
     adds read and write permissions for everybody, while retaining
     executable bits on directories or on any other file already marked
     as executable.

@{b}--multi-volume@{ub}
@{b}-M@{ub}
     Informs @{b}tar@{ub} that it should create or otherwise operate on a
     multi-volume @{b}tar@{ub} archive.  .

@{b}--new-volume-script@{ub}
     (see -info-script)

@{b}--newer=DATE@{ub}
@{b}--after-date=DATE@{ub}
@{b}-N@{ub}
     When creating an archive, @{b}tar@{ub} will only add files that have changed
     since DATE.  .

@{b}--newer-mtime@{ub}
     In conjunction with @{b}--newer@{ub}, @{b}tar@{ub} will only add files whose
     contents have changed (as opposed to just @{b}--newer@{ub}, which will also
     back up files for which any status information has changed).

@{b}--no-recursion@{ub}
     With this option, @{b}tar@{ub} will not recurse into directories unless a
     directory is explicitly named as an argument to @{b}tar@{ub}.  .

@{b}--null@{ub}
     When @{b}tar@{ub} is using the @{b}--files-from@{ub} option, this option instructs
     @{b}tar@{ub} to expect filenames terminated with @{b}NUL@{ub}, so @{b}tar@{ub} can correctly
     work with file names that contain newlines.  .

@{b}--numeric-owner@{ub}
     This option will notify @{b}tar@{ub} that it should use numeric user and
     group IDs when creating a @{b}tar@{ub} file, rather than names.  .

@{b}--old-archive@{ub}
     (See @{b}--portability@{ub}; .)

@{b}--one-file-system@{ub}
@{b}-l@{ub}
     Used when creating an archive.  Prevents @{b}tar@{ub} from recursing into
     directories that are on different file systems from the current
     directory.  .

@{b}--owner=USER@{ub}
     Specifies that @{b}tar@{ub} should use USER as the owner of members when
     creating archives, instead of the user associated with the source
     file.  USER is first decoded as a user symbolic name, but if this
     interpretation fails, it has to be a decimal numeric user ID.  .

     There is no value indicating a missing number, and @{b}0@{ub} usually means
     @{b}root@{ub}.  Some people like to force @{b}0@{ub} as the value to offer in their
     distributions for the owner of files, because the @{b}root@{ub} user is
     anonymous anyway, so that might as well be the owner of anonymous
     archives.

@{b}--portability@{ub}
@{b}--old-archive@{ub}
@{b}-o@{ub}
     Tells @{b}tar@{ub} to create an archive that is compatible with Unix V7
     @{b}tar@{ub}.  .

@{b}--posix@{ub}
     Instructs @{b}tar@{ub} to create a POSIX compliant @{b}tar@{ub} archive.  .

@{b}--preserve@{ub}
     Synonymous with specifying both @{b}--preserve-permissions@{ub} and
     @{b}--same-order@{ub}.  .

@{b}--preserve-order@{ub}
     (See @{b}--same-order@{ub}; see @{"Reading" link "Reading"}.)

@{b}--preserve-permissions@{ub}
@{b}--same-permissions@{ub}
@{b}-p@{ub}
     When @{b}tar@{ub} is extracting an archive, it normally subtracts the users'
     umask from the permissions specified in the archive and uses that
     number as the permissions to create the destination file.
     Specifying this option instructs @{b}tar@{ub} that it should use the
     permissions directly from the archive.  See @{"Writing" link "Writing"}.

@{b}--read-full-records@{ub}
@{b}-B@{ub}
     Specifies that @{b}tar@{ub} should reblock its input, for reading from
     pipes on systems with buggy implementations.  See @{"Reading" link "Reading"}.

@{b}--record-size=SIZE@{ub}
     Instructs @{b}tar@{ub} to use SIZE bytes per record when accessing the
     archive.  .

@{b}--recursive-unlink@{ub}
     Similar to the @{b}--unlink-first@{ub} option, removing existing directory
     hierarchies before extracting directories of the same name from
     the archive.  See @{"Writing" link "Writing"}.

@{b}--remove-files@{ub}
     Directs @{b}tar@{ub} to remove the source file from the file system after
     appending it to an archive.  .

@{b}--rsh-command=CMD@{ub}
     Notifies @{b}tar@{ub} that is should use CMD to communicate with remote
     devices.  .

@{b}--same-order@{ub}
@{b}--preserve-order@{ub}
@{b}-s@{ub}
     This option is an optimization for @{b}tar@{ub} when running on machines
     with small amounts of memory.  It informs @{b}tar@{ub} that the list of file
     arguments has already been sorted to match the order of files in
     the archive.  See @{"Reading" link "Reading"}.

@{b}--same-owner@{ub}
     When extracting an archive, @{b}tar@{ub} will attempt to preserve the owner
     specified in the @{b}tar@{ub} archive with this option present.  .

@{b}--same-permissions@{ub}
     (See @{b}--preserve-permissions@{ub}; see @{"Writing" link "Writing"}.)

@{b}--show-omitted-dirs@{ub}
     Instructs @{b}tar@{ub} to mention directories its skipping over when
     operating on a @{b}tar@{ub} archive.  .

@{b}--sparse@{ub}
@{b}-S@{ub}
     Invokes a GNU extension when adding files to an archive that
     handles sparse files efficiently.  .

@{b}--starting-file=NAME@{ub}
@{b}-K NAME@{ub}
     This option affects extraction only; @{b}tar@{ub} will skip extracting
     files in the archive until it finds one that matches NAME.  See
     @{"Scarce" link "Scarce"}.

@{b}--suffix=SUFFIX@{ub}
     Alters the suffix @{b}tar@{ub} uses when backing up files from the default
     @{b}~@{ub}.  .

@{b}--tape-length=NUM@{ub}
@{b}-L NUM@{ub}
     Specifies the length of tapes that @{b}tar@{ub} is writing as being
     NUM x 1024 bytes long.  .

@{b}--to-stdout@{ub}
@{b}-O@{ub}
     During extraction, @{b}tar@{ub} will extract files to stdout rather than to
     the file system.  See @{"Writing" link "Writing"}.

@{b}--totals@{ub}
     Displays the total number of bytes written after creating an
     archive.  .

@{b}--touch@{ub}
@{b}-m@{ub}
     Sets the modification time of extracted files to the extraction
     time, rather than the modification time stored in the archive.
     See @{"Writing" link "Writing"}.

@{b}--uncompress@{ub}
     (See @{b}--compress@{ub}; .)

@{b}--ungzip@{ub}
     (See @{b}--gzip@{ub}; .)

@{b}--unlink-first@{ub}
@{b}-U@{ub}
     Directs @{b}tar@{ub} to remove the corresponding file from the file system
     before extracting it from the archive.  See @{"Writing" link "Writing"}.

@{b}--use-compress-program=PROG@{ub}
     Instructs @{b}tar@{ub} to access the archive through PROG, which is
     presumed to be a compression program of some sort.  .

@{b}--verbose@{ub}
@{b}-v@{ub}
     Specifies that @{b}tar@{ub} should be more verbose about the operations its
     performing.  This option can be specified multiple times for some
     operations to increase the amount of information displayed.  .

@{b}--verify@{ub}
@{b}-W@{ub}
     Verifies that the archive was correctly written when creating an
     archive.  .

@{b}--version@{ub}
@{b}     tar@{ub} will print an informational message about what version it is
     and a copyright message, some credits, and then exit.  .

@{b}--volno-file=FILE@{ub}
     Used in conjunction with @{b}--multi-volume@{ub}.  @{b}tar@{ub} will keep track of
     which volume of a multi-volume archive its working in FILE.  .


@endnode

