@node "help" "tar.guide/help"
@next "verbose"
@prev "All Options"
@toc "tar invocation"

GNU @{b}tar@{ub} documentation
=====================

   Being careful, the first thing is really checking that you are using
GNU @{b}tar@{ub}, indeed.  The @{b}--version@{ub} option will generate a message giving
confirmation that you are using GNU @{b}tar@{ub}, with the precise version of
GNU @{b}tar@{ub} you are using.  @{b}tar@{ub} identifies itself and prints the version
number to the standard output, then immediately exits successfully,
without doing anything else, ignoring all other options.  For example,
@{b}tar --version@{ub} might return:

     tar (GNU tar) 1.12

The first occurrence of @{b}tar@{ub} in the result above is the program name in
the package (for example, @{b}rmt@{ub} is another program), while the second
occurrence of @{b}tar@{ub} is the name of the package itself, containing
possibly many programs.  The package is currently named @{b}tar@{ub}, after the
name of the main program it contains(1).

   Another thing you might want to do is checking the spelling or
meaning of some particular @{b}tar@{ub} option, without resorting to this manual,
for once you have carefully read it.  GNU @{b}tar@{ub} has a short help feature,
triggerable through the @{b}--help@{ub} option.  By using this option, @{b}tar@{ub} will
print a usage message listing all available options on standard output,
then exit successfully, without doing anything else and ignoring all
other options.  Even if this is only a brief summary, it may be several
screens long.  So, if you are not using some kind of scrollable window,
you might prefer to use something like:

     $ tar --help | less

presuming, here, that you like using @{b}less@{ub} for a pager.  Other popular
pagers are @{b}more@{ub} and @{b}pg@{ub}.  If you know about some KEYWORD which interests
you and do not want to read all the @{b}--help@{ub} output, another common idiom
is doing:

     tar --help | grep KEYWORD

for getting only the pertinent lines.

   The perceptive reader would have noticed some contradiction in the
previous paragraphs.  It is written that both @{b}--version@{ub} and @{b}--help@{ub}
print something, and have all other options ignored.  In fact, they
cannot ignore each other, and one of them has to win.  We do not
specify which is stronger, here; experiment if you really wonder!

   The short help output is quite succint, and you might have to get
back to the full documentation for precise points.  If you are reading
this paragraph, you already have the @{b}tar@{ub} manual in some form.  This
manual is available in printed form, as a kind of small book.  It may
printed out of the GNU @{b}tar@{ub} distribution, provided you have TeX already
installed somewhere, and a laser printer around.  Just configure the
distribution, execute the command @{b}make dvi@{ub}, then print @{b}doc/tar.dvi@{ub} the
usual way (contact your local guru to know how).  If GNU @{b}tar@{ub} has been
conveniently installed at your place, this manual is also available in
interactive, hypertextual form as an Info file.  Just call @{b}info tar@{ub} or,
if you do not have the @{b}info@{ub} program handy, use the Info reader provided
within GNU Emacs, calling @{b}tar@{ub} from the main Info menu.

   There is currently no @{b}man@{ub} page for GNU @{b}tar@{ub}.  If you observe such a
@{b}man@{ub} page on the system you are running, either it does not long to GNU
@{b}tar@{ub}, or it has not been produced by GNU.  Currently, GNU @{b}tar@{ub}
documentation is provided in Texinfo format only, if we except, of
course, the short result of @{b}tar --help@{ub}.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) There are plans to merge the @{b}cpio@{ub} and @{b}tar@{ub} packages into a single
one which would be called @{b}paxutils@{ub}.  So, who knows if, one of this days,
the @{b}--version@{ub} would not yield @{b}tar (GNU paxutils) 3.2@{ub}


@endnode

@node "verbose" "tar.guide/verbose"
@next "interactive"
@prev "help"
@toc "tar invocation"

Checking @{b}tar@{ub} progress
=====================

   Typically, @{b}tar@{ub} performs most operations without reporting any
information to the user except error messages.  When using @{b}tar@{ub} with
many options, particularly ones with complicated or
difficult-to-predict behavior, it is possible to make serious mistakes.
@{b}tar@{ub} provides several options that make observing @{b}tar@{ub} easier.  These
options cause @{b}tar@{ub} to print information as it progresses in its job, and
you might want to use them just for being more careful about what is
going on, or merely for entertaining yourself.  If you have encountered
a problem when operating on an archive, however, you may need more
information than just an error message in order to solve the problem.
The following options can be helpful diagnostic tools.

   Normally, the @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}) command to list an archive prints just the
file names (one per line) and the other commands are silent.  When used
with most operations, the @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) option causes @{b}tar@{ub} to print the
name of each file or archive member as it is processed.  This and the
other options which make @{b}tar@{ub} print status information can be useful in
monitoring @{b}tar@{ub}.

   With @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) or @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}), @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) used once
just prints the names of the files or members as they are processed.
Using it twice causes @{b}tar@{ub} to print a longer listing (reminiscent of @{b}ls
-l@{ub}) for each member.  Since @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}) already prints the names of the
members, @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) used once with @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}) causes @{b}tar@{ub} to print
an @{b}ls -l@{ub} type listing of the files in the archive.  The following
examples both extract members with long list output:

     $ tar --extract --file=archive.tar --verbose --verbose
     $ tar xvv archive.tar

   Verbose output appears on the standard output except when an archive
is being written to the standard output, as with @{b}tar --create --file=-
--verbose@{ub} (@{b}tar cfv -@{ub}, or even @{b}tar cv@{ub}--if the installer let standard
output be the default archive).  In that case @{b}tar@{ub} writes verbose output
to the standard error stream.

   The @{b}--totals@{ub} option--which is only meaningful when used with
@{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub})--causes @{b}tar@{ub} to print the total amount written to the
archive, after it has been fully created.

   The @{b}--checkpoint@{ub} option prints an occasional message as @{b}tar@{ub} reads or
writes the archive.  In fact, it print directory names while reading
the archive.  It is designed for those who don't need the more detailed
(and voluminous) output of @{b}--block-number@{ub} (@{b}-R@{ub}), but do want visual
confirmation that @{b}tar@{ub} is actually making forward progress.

   The @{b}--show-omitted-dirs@{ub} option, when reading an archive--with @{b}--list@{ub}
(@{b}-t@{ub}) or @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}), for example--causes a message to be
printed for each directory in the archive which is skipped.  This
happens regardless of the reason for skipping: the directory might not
have been named on the command line (implicitly or explicitly), it
might be excluded by the use of the @{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub} option, or some
other reason.

   If @{b}--block-number@{ub} (@{b}-R@{ub}) is used, @{b}tar@{ub} prints, along with every message
it would normally produce, the block number within the archive where
the message was triggered.  Also, supplementary messages are triggered
when reading blocks full of NULs, or when hitting end of file on the
archive.  As of now, if the archive if properly terminated with a NUL
block, the reading of the file may stop before end of file is met, so
the position of end of file will not usually show when @{b}--block-number@{ub}
(@{b}-R@{ub}) is used.  Note that GNU @{b}tar@{ub} drains the archive before exiting when
reading the archive from a pipe.

   This option is especially useful when reading damaged archives, since
it helps pinpoint the damaged sections.  It can also be used with
@{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}) when listing a file-system backup tape, allowing you to
choose among several backup tapes when retrieving a file later, in
favor of the tape where the file appears earliest (closest to the front
of the tape).  .


@endnode

@node "interactive" "tar.guide/interactive"
@prev "verbose"
@toc "tar invocation"

Asking for Confirmation During Operations
=========================================

   Typically, @{b}tar@{ub} carries out a command without stopping for further
instructions.  In some situations however, you may want to exclude some
files and archive members from the operation (for instance if disk or
storage space is tight).  You can do this by excluding certain files
automatically (see @{"Choosing" link "Choosing"}), or by performing an operation
interactively, using the @{b}--interactive@{ub} (@{b}-w@{ub}) option.  @{b}tar@{ub} also accepts
@{b}--confirmation@{ub} for this option.

   When the @{b}--interactive@{ub} (@{b}-w@{ub}) option is specified, before reading,
writing, or deleting files, @{b}tar@{ub} first prints a message for each such
file, telling what operation it intends to take, then asks for
confirmation on the terminal.  The actions which require confirmation
include adding a file to the archive, extracting a file from the
archive, deleting a file from the archive, and deleting a file from
disk.  To confirm the action, you must type a line of input beginning
with @{b}y@{ub}.  If your input line begins with anything other than @{b}y@{ub}, @{b}tar@{ub}
skips that file.

   If @{b}tar@{ub} is reading the archive from the standard input, @{b}tar@{ub} opens the
file @{b}/dev/tty@{ub} to support the interactive communications.

   Verbose output is normally sent to standard output, separate from
other error messages.  However, if the archive is produced directly on
standard output, then verbose output is mixed with errors on @{b}stderr@{ub}.
Producing the archive on standard output may be used as a way to avoid
using disk space, when the archive is soon to be consumed by another
process reading it, say.  Some people felt the need of producing an
archive on stdout, still willing to segregate between verbose output
and error output.  A possible approach would be using a named pipe to
receive the archive, and having the consumer process to read from that
named pipe.  This has the advantage of letting standard output free to
receive verbose output, all separate from errors.


@endnode

