The Five Advanced @{b}tar@{ub} Operations
--------------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   In the last chapter, you learned about the first three operations to
@{b}tar@{ub}.  This chapter presents the remaining five operations to @{b}tar@{ub}:
@{b}--append@{ub}, @{b}--update@{ub}, @{b}--concatenate@{ub}, @{b}--delete@{ub}, and @{b}--compare@{ub}.

   You are not likely to use these operations as frequently as those
covered in the last chapter; however, since they perform specialized
functions, they are quite useful when you do need to use them.  We will
give examples using the same directory and files that you created in
the last chapter.  As you may recall, the directory is called @{b}practice@{ub},
the files are @{b}jazz@{ub}, @{b}blues@{ub}, @{b}folk@{ub}, @{b}rock@{ub}, and the two archive files you
created are @{b}collection.tar@{ub} and @{b}music.tar@{ub}.

   We will also use the archive files @{b}afiles.tar@{ub} and @{b}bfiles.tar@{ub}.
@{b}afiles.tar@{ub} contains the members @{b}apple@{ub}, @{b}angst@{ub}, and @{b}aspic@{ub}.  @{b}bfiles.tar@{ub}
contains the members @{b}./birds@{ub}, @{b}baboon@{ub}, and @{b}./box@{ub}.

   Unless we state otherwise, all practicing you do and examples you
follow in this chapter will take place in the @{b}practice@{ub} directory that
you created in the previous chapter; see @{"prepare for examples" link "prepare for examples"}.  (Below
in this section, we will remind you of the state of the examples where
the last chapter left them.)

   The five operations that we will cover in this chapter are:

@{b}--append@{ub}
@{b}-r@{ub}
     Add new entries to an archive that already exists.

@{b}--update@{ub}
@{b}-r@{ub}
     Add more recent copies of archive members to the end of an
     archive, if they exist.

@{b}--concatenate@{ub}
@{b}--catenate@{ub}
@{b}-A@{ub}
     Add one or more pre-existing archives to the end of another
     archive.

@{b}--delete@{ub}
     Delete items from an archive (does not work on tapes).

@{b}--compare@{ub}
@{b}--diff@{ub}
@{b}-d@{ub}
     Compare archive members to their counterparts in the file system.


