@node "append" "tar.guide/append"
@next "update"
@prev "current state"
@toc "Advanced tar"

How to Add Files to Existing Archives: @{b}--append@{ub}
-----------------------------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   If you want to add files to an existing archive, you don't need to
create a new archive; you can use @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}).  The archive must
already exist in order to use @{b}--append@{ub}.  (A related operation is the
@{b}--update@{ub} operation; you can use this to add newer versions of archive
members to an existing archive.  To learn how to do this with @{b}--update@{ub},
see @{"update" link "update"}.)

   If you use @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}) to add a file that has the same name as an
archive member to an archive containing that archive member, then the
old member is not deleted.  What does happen, however, is somewhat
complex.  @{b}tar@{ub} @{i}allows@{ui} you to have infinite numbers of files with the
same name.  Some operations treat these same-named members no
differently than any other set of archive members: for example, if you
view an archive with @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}), you will see all of those members
listed, with their modification times, owners, etc.

   Other operations don't deal with these members as perfectly as you
might prefer; if you were to use @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}) to extract the
archive, only the most recently added copy of a member with the same
name as four other members would end up in the working directory.  This
is because @{b}--extract@{ub} extracts an archive in the order the members
appeared in the archive; the most recently archived members will be
extracted last.  Additionally, an extracted member will @{i}overwrite@{ui} a
file of the same name which existed in the directory already, and @{b}tar@{ub}
will not prompt you about this.  Thus, only the most recently archived
member will end up being extracted, as it will overwrite the one
extracted before it, and so on.

   There are a few ways to get around this.  .

   If you want to replace an archive member, use @{b}--delete@{ub} to delete the
member you want to remove from the archive, , and then use @{b}--append@{ub} to
add the member you want to be in the archive.  Note that you can not
change the order of the archive; the most recently added member will
still appear last.  In this sense, you cannot truely "replace" one
member with another.  (Replacing one member with another will not work
on certain types of media, such as tapes; see @{"delete" link "delete"} and @{"Media" link "Media"}, for
more information.)


 @{" appending files            " link "appending files"}  Appending Files to an Archive
 @{" multiple                   " link "multiple"}


@endnode

@node "appending files" "tar.guide/appending files"
@next "multiple"
@prev "append"
@toc "append"

Appending Files to an Archive
.............................

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   The simplest way to add a file to an already existing archive is the
@{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}) operation, which writes specified files into the archive
whether or not they are already among the archived files.  When you use
@{b}--append@{ub}, you @{i}must@{ui} specify file name arguments, as there is no default.
If you specify a file that already exists in the archive, another copy
of the file will be added to the end of the archive.  As with other
operations, the member names of the newly added files will be exactly
the same as their names given on the command line.  The @{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub})
option will print out the names of the files as they are written into
the archive.

@{b}   --append@{ub} cannot be performed on some tape drives, unfortunately, due
to deficiencies in the formats those tape drives use.  The archive must
be a valid @{b}tar@{ub} archive, or else the results of using this operation
will be unpredictable.  See @{"Media" link "Media"}.

   To demonstrate using @{b}--append@{ub} to add a file to an archive, create a
file called @{b}rock@{ub} in the @{b}practice@{ub} directory.  Make sure you are in the
@{b}practice@{ub} directory.  Then, run the following @{b}tar@{ub} command to add @{b}rock@{ub} to
@{b}collection.tar@{ub}:

     $ tar --append --file=collection.tar rock

If you now use the @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}) operation, you will see that @{b}rock@{ub} has
been added to the archive:

     $ tar --list --file=collection.tar
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     28 1996-10-18 16:31 jazz
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     21 1996-09-23 16:44 blues
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     20 1996-09-23 16:44 folk
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     20 1996-09-23 16:44 rock


@endnode

@node "multiple" "tar.guide/multiple"
@prev "appending files"
@toc "append"

Multiple Files with the Same Name
.................................

   You can use @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}) to add copies of files which have been
updated since the archive was created.  (However, we do not recommend
doing this since there is another @{b}tar@{ub} option called @{b}--update@{ub}; see
@{"update" link "update"} for more information.  We describe this use of @{b}--append@{ub} here
for the sake of completeness.)   When you extract the archive, the
older version will be effectively lost.  This works because files are
extracted from an archive in the order in which they were archived.
Thus, when the archive is extracted, a file archived later in time will
overwrite a file of the same name which was archived earlier, even
though the older version of the file will remain in the archive unless
you delete all versions of the file.

   Supposing you change the file @{b}blues@{ub} and then append the changed
version to @{b}collection.tar@{ub}.  As you saw above, the original @{b}blues@{ub} is in
the archive @{b}collection.tar@{ub}.  If you change the file and append the new
version of the file to the archive, there will be two copies in the
archive.  When you extract the archive, the older version of the file
will be extracted first, and then overwritten by the newer version when
it is extracted.

   You can append the new, changed copy of the file @{b}blues@{ub} to the
archive in this way:

     $ tar --append --verbose --file=collection.tar blues
     blues

Because you specified the @{b}--verbose@{ub} option, @{b}tar@{ub} has printed the name of
the file being appended as it was acted on.  Now list the contents of
the archive:

     $ tar --list --verbose --file=collection.tar
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     28 1996-10-18 16:31 jazz
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     21 1996-09-23 16:44 blues
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     20 1996-09-23 16:44 folk
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     20 1996-09-23 16:44 rock
     -rw-rw-rw- me user     58 1996-10-24 18:30 blues

The newest version of @{b}blues@{ub} is now at the end of the archive (note the
different creation dates and file sizes).  If you extract the archive,
the older version of the file @{b}blues@{ub} will be overwritten by the newer
version.  You can confirm this by extracting the archive and running @{b}ls@{ub}
on the directory.  See @{"Writing" link "Writing"} for more information.  (@{i}Please note:@{ui}
This is the case unless you employ the @{b}--backup@{ub} option; .)


@endnode

@node "update" "tar.guide/update"
@next "concatenate"
@prev "append"
@toc "Advanced tar"

Updating an Archive
-------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   In the previous section, you learned how to use @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}) to add
a file to an existing archive.  A related operation is @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}).
The @{b}--update@{ub} operation updates a @{b}tar@{ub} archive by comparing the date of
the specified archive members against the date of the file with the
same name.  If the file has been modified more recently than the
archive member, then the newer version of the file is added to the
archive (as with @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub})).

   Unfortunately, you cannot use @{b}--update@{ub} with magnetic tape drives.
The operation will fail.

   Both @{b}--update@{ub} and @{b}--append@{ub} work by adding to the end of the archive.
When you extract a file from the archive, only the version stored last
will wind up in the file system, unless you use the @{b}--backup@{ub} option ().


 @{" how to update " link "how to update"}


@endnode

@node "how to update" "tar.guide/how to update"
@prev "update"
@toc "update"

How to Update an Archive Using @{b}--update@{ub}
.......................................

   You must use file name arguments with the @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}) operation.
If you don't specify any files, @{b}tar@{ub} won't act on any files and won't
tell you that it didn't do anything (which may end up confusing you).

   To see the @{b}--update@{ub} option at work, create a new file, @{b}classical@{ub}, in
your practice directory, and some extra text to the file @{b}blues@{ub}, using
any text editor.  Then invoke @{b}tar@{ub} with the @{b}update@{ub} operation and the
@{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}) option specified, using the names of all the files in
the practice directory as file name arguments:

     $ tar --update -v -f collection.tar blues folk rock classical
     blues
     classical
     $

Because we have specified verbose mode, @{b}tar@{ub} prints out the names of the
files it is working on, which in this case are the names of the files
that needed to be updated.  If you run @{b}tar --list@{ub} and look at the
archive, you will see @{b}blues@{ub} and @{b}classical@{ub} at its end.  There will be a
total of two versions of the member @{b}blues@{ub}; the one at the end will be
newer and larger, since you added text before updating it.

   (The reason @{b}tar@{ub} does not overwrite the older file when updating it
is because writing to the middle of a section of tape is a difficult
process.  Tapes are not designed to go backward.  See @{"Media" link "Media"} for more
information about tapes.

   @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}) is not suitable for performing backups for two
reasons: it does not change directory content entries, and it lengthens
the archive every time it is used.  The GNU @{b}tar@{ub} options intended
specifically for backups are more efficient.  If you need to run
backups, please consult @{"Backups" link "Backups"}.


@endnode

@node "concatenate" "tar.guide/concatenate"
@next "delete"
@prev "update"
@toc "Advanced tar"

Combining Archives with @{b}--concatenate@{ub}
-------------------------------------

   Sometimes it may be convenient to add a second archive onto the end
of an archive rather than adding individual files to the archive.  To
add one or more archives to the end of another archive, you should use
the @{b}--concatenate@{ub} (@{b}--catenate@{ub}, @{b}-A@{ub}) operation.

   To use @{b}--concatenate@{ub}, name the archives to be concatenated on the
command line.  (Nothing happens if you don't list any.)  The members,
and their member names, will be copied verbatim from those archives.  If
this causes multiple members to have the same name, it does not delete
any members; all the members with the same name coexist.  For
information on how this affects reading the archive, .

   To demonstrate how @{b}--concatenate@{ub} works, create two small archives
called @{b}bluesrock.tar@{ub} and @{b}folkjazz.tar@{ub}, using the relevant files from
@{b}practice@{ub}:

     $ tar -cvf bluesrock.tar blues rock
     blues
     classical
     $ tar -cvf folkjazz.tar folk jazz
     folk
     jazz

If you like, You can run @{b}tar --list@{ub} to make sure the archives contain
what they are supposed to:

     $ tar -tvf bluesrock.tar
     -rw-rw-rw- melissa user    105 1997-01-21 19:42 blues
     -rw-rw-rw- melissa user     33 1997-01-20 15:34 rock
     $ tar -tvf folkjazz.tar
     -rw-rw-rw- melissa user     20 1996-09-23 16:44 folk
     -rw-rw-rw- melissa user     65 1997-01-30 14:15 jazz

   We can concatenate these two archives with @{b}tar@{ub}:

     $ cd ..
     $ tar --concatenate --file=bluesrock.tar jazzfolk.tar

   If you now list the contents of the @{b}bluesclass.tar@{ub}, you will see
that now it also contains the archive members of @{b}jazzfolk.tar@{ub}:

     $ tar --list --file=bluesrock.tar
     blues
     rock
     jazz
     folk

   When you use @{b}--concatenate@{ub}, the source and target archives must
already exist and must have been created using compatable format
parameters ().  The new, concatenated archive will be called by the
same name as the first archive listed on the command line.

   Like @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}), this operation cannot be performed on some tape
drives, due to deficiencies in the formats those tape drives use.

   It may seem more intuitive to you to want or try to use @{b}cat@{ub} to
concatenate two archives instead of using the @{b}--concatenate@{ub} operation;
after all, @{b}cat@{ub} is the utility for combining files.

   However, @{b}tar@{ub} archives incorporate an end-of-file marker which must
be removed if the concatenated archives are to be read properly as one
archive.  @{b}--concatenate@{ub} removes the end-of-archive marker from the
target archive before each new archive is appended.  If you use @{b}cat@{ub} to
combine the archives, the result will not be a valid @{b}tar@{ub} format
archive.  If you need to retrieve files from an archive that was added
to using the @{b}cat@{ub} utility, use the @{b}--ignore-zeros@{ub} (@{b}-i@{ub}) option.  See
@{"Ignore Zeros" link "Ignore Zeros"} for further information on dealing with archives
improperly combined using the @{b}cat@{ub} shell utility.

   You must specify the source archives using @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f
ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) (see @{"file" link "file"}).  If you do not specify the target archive,
@{b}tar@{ub} uses the value of the environment variable @{b}TAPE@{ub}, or, if this has
not been set, the default archive name.


@endnode

@node "delete" "tar.guide/delete"
@next "compare"
@prev "concatenate"
@toc "Advanced tar"

Removing Archive Members Using @{b}--delete@{ub}
---------------------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   You can remove members from an archive by using the @{b}--delete@{ub} option.
Specify the name of the archive with @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f
ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) and then specify the names of the members to be deleted;
if you list no member names, nothing will be deleted.  The @{b}--verbose@{ub}
(@{b}-v@{ub}) option will cause @{b}tar@{ub} to print the names of the members as they
are deleted.  As with @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}), you must give the exact
member names when using @{b}tar --delete@{ub}.  @{b}--delete@{ub} will remove all
versions of the named file from the archive.  The @{b}--delete@{ub} operation
can run very slowly.

   Unlike other operations, @{b}--delete@{ub} has no short form.

   This operation will rewrite the archive.  You can only use @{b}--delete@{ub}
on an archive if the archive device allows you to write to any point on
the media, such as a disk; because of this, it does not work on
magnetic tapes.  Do not try to delete an archive member from a magnetic
tape; the action will not succeed, and you will be likely to scramble
the archive and damage your tape.  There is no safe way (except by
completely re-writing the archive) to delete files from most kinds of
magnetic tape.  See @{"Media" link "Media"}.

   To delete all versions of the file @{b}blues@{ub} from the archive
@{b}collection.tar@{ub} in the @{b}practice@{ub} directory, make sure you are in that
directory, and then,

     $ tar --list --file=collection.tar
     blues
     folk
     jazz
     rock
     practice/blues
     practice/folk
     practice/jazz
     practice/rock
     practice/blues
     $ tar --delete --file=collection.tar blues
     $ tar --list --file=collection.tar
     folk
     jazz
     rock
     $

   The @{b}--delete@{ub} option has been reported to work properly when @{b}tar@{ub} acts
as a filter from @{b}stdin@{ub} to @{b}stdout@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "compare" "tar.guide/compare"
@prev "delete"
@toc "Advanced tar"

Comparing Archive Members with the File System
----------------------------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   The @{b}--compare@{ub} (@{b}-d@{ub}), or @{b}--diff@{ub} operation compares specified archive
members against files with the same names, and then reports differences
in file size, mode, owner, modification date and contents.  You should
@{i}only@{ui} specify archive member names, not file names.  If you do not name
any members, then @{b}tar@{ub} will compare the entire archive.  If a file is
represented in the archive but does not exist in the file system, @{b}tar@{ub}
reports a difference.

   You have to specify the record size of the archive when modifying an
archive with a non-default record size.

@{b}   tar@{ub} ignores files in the file system that do not have corresponding
members in the archive.

   The following example compares the archive members @{b}rock@{ub}, @{b}blues@{ub} and
@{b}funk@{ub} in the archive @{b}bluesrock.tar@{ub} with files of the same name in the
file system.  (Note that there is no file, @{b}funk@{ub}; @{b}tar@{ub} will report an
error message.)

     $ tar --compare --file=bluesrock.tar rock blues funk
     rock
     blues
     tar: funk not found in archive

Depending on the system where you are running @{b}tar@{ub} and the version you
are running, @{b}tar@{ub} may have a different error message, such as:

     funk: does not exist

   The spirit behind the @{b}--compare@{ub} (@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}) option is to check
whether the archive represents the current state of files on disk, more
than validating the integrity of the archive media.  For this later
goal, See @{"verify" link "verify"}.


@endnode

