Ignoring Blocks of Zeros
........................

   Normally, @{b}tar@{ub} stops reading when it encounters a block of zeros
between file entries (which usually indicates the end of the archive).
@{b}--ignore-zeros@{ub} (@{b}-i@{ub}) allows @{b}tar@{ub} to completely read an archive which
contains a block of zeros before the end (i.e. a damaged archive, or
one which was created by @{b}cat@{ub}-ing several archives together).

   The @{b}--ignore-zeros@{ub} (@{b}-i@{ub}) option is turned off by default because many
versions of @{b}tar@{ub} write garbage after the end-of-archive entry, since
that part of the media is never supposed to be read.  GNU @{b}tar@{ub} does not
write after the end of an archive, but seeks to maintain compatablity
among archiving utilities.

@{b}--ignore-zeros@{ub}
@{b}-i@{ub}
     To ignore blocks of zeros (ie. end-of-archive entries) which may be
     encountered while reading an archive.  Use in conjunction with
     @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}) or @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}).


@endnode

