Choosing and Naming Archive Files
=================================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   By default, @{b}tar@{ub} uses an archive file name that was compiled when it
was built on the system; usually this name refers to some physical tape
drive on the machine.  However, the person who installed @{b}tar@{ub} on the
system may not set the default to a meaningful value as far as most
users are concerned.  As a result, you will usually want to tell @{b}tar@{ub}
where to find (or create) the archive.  The @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f
ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) option allows you to either specify or name a file to use
as the archive instead of the default archive file location.

@{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}
@{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}
     Name the archive to create or operate on.  Use in conjunction with
     any operation.

   For example, in this @{b}tar@{ub} command,

     $ tar -cvf collection.tar blues folk jazz

@{b}collection.tar@{ub} is the name of the archive.  It must directly follow the
@{b}-f@{ub} option, since whatever directly follows @{b}-f@{ub} @{i}will@{ui} end up naming the
archive.  If you neglect to specify an archive name, you may end up
overwriting a file in the working directory with the archive you create
since @{b}tar@{ub} will use this file's name for the archive name.

   An archive can be saved as a file in the file system, sent through a
pipe or over a network, or written to an I/O device such as a tape,
floppy disk, or CD write drive.

   If you do not name the archive, @{b}tar@{ub} uses the value of the
environment variable @{b}TAPE@{ub} as the file name for the archive.  If that is
not available, @{b}tar@{ub} uses a default, compiled-in archive name, usually
that for tape unit zero (ie. @{b}/dev/tu00@{ub}).  @{b}tar@{ub} always needs an archive
name.

   If you use @{b}-@{ub} as an ARCHIVE-NAME, @{b}tar@{ub} reads the archive from standard
input (when listing or extracting files), or writes it to standard
output (when creating an archive).  If you use @{b}-@{ub} as an ARCHIVE-NAME
when modifying an archive, @{b}tar@{ub} reads the original archive from its
standard input and writes the entire new archive to its standard output.

     $ cd sourcedir; tar -cf - . | (cd targetdir; tar -xf -)

   To specify an archive file on a device attached to a remote machine,
use the following:

     --file=HOSTNAME:/DEV/FILE NAME

@{b}tar@{ub} will complete the remote connection, if possible, and prompt you
for a username and password.  If you use @{b}--file=@HOSTNAME:/DEV/FILE
NAME@{ub}, @{b}tar@{ub} will complete the remote connection, if possible, using your
username as the username on the remote machine.

   If the archive file name includes a colon (@{b}:@{ub}), then it is assumed to
be a file on another machine.  If the archive file is @{b}USER@HOST:FILE@{ub},
then FILE is used on the host HOST.  The remote host is accessed using
the @{b}rsh@{ub} program, with a username of USER.  If the username is omitted
(along with the @{b}\@@{ub} sign), then your user name will be used.  (This is the
normal @{b}rsh@{ub} behavior.)  It is necessary for the remote machine, in
addition to permitting your @{b}rsh@{ub} access, to have the @{b}/usr/ucb/rmt@{ub}
program installed.  If you need to use a file whose name includes a
colon, then the remote tape drive behavior can be inhibited by using
the @{b}--force-local@{ub} option.

   When the archive is being created to @{b}/dev/null@{ub}, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} tries to
minimize input and output operations.  The Amanda backup system, when
used with GNU @{b}tar@{ub}, has an initial sizing pass which uses this feature.


@endnode

@node "Selecting Archive Members" "tar.guide/Selecting Archive Members"
@next "files"
@prev "file"
@toc "Choosing"

Selecting Archive Members
=========================

@{i}   File Name arguments@{ui} specify which files in the file system @{b}tar@{ub}
operates on, when creating or adding to an archive, or which archive
members @{b}tar@{ub} operates on, when reading or deleting from an archive.  See
@{"Operations" link "Operations"}.

   To specify file names, you can include them as the last arguments on
the command line, as follows:
     tar OPERATION [OPTION1 OPTION2 ...] [FILE NAME-1 FILE NAME-2 ...]

   If you specify a directory name as a file name argument, all the
files in that directory are operated on by @{b}tar@{ub}.

   If you do not specify files when @{b}tar@{ub} is invoked with @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}),
@{b}tar@{ub} operates on all the non-directory files in the working directory.
If you specify either @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}) or @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}), @{b}tar@{ub}
operates on all the archive members in the archive.  If you specify any
operation other than one of these three, @{b}tar@{ub} does nothing.

   By default, @{b}tar@{ub} takes file names from the command line.  However,
there are other ways to specify file or member names, or to modify the
manner in which @{b}tar@{ub} selects the files or members upon which to operate;
.  In general, these methods work both for specifying the names of
files and archive members.


@endnode

@node "files" "tar.guide/files"
@next "exclude"
@prev "Selecting Archive Members"
@toc "Choosing"

Reading Names from a File
=========================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   Instead of giving the names of files or archive members on the
command line, you can put the names into a file, and then use the
@{b}--files-from=FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub} (@{b}-T FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub}) option to @{b}tar@{ub}.  Give the
name of the file which contains the list of files to include as the
argument to @{b}--files-from@{ub}.  In the list, the file names should be
separated by newlines.  You will frequently use this option when you
have generated the list of files to archive with the @{b}find@{ub} utility.

@{b}--files-from=FILE NAME@{ub}
@{b}-T FILE NAME@{ub}
     Get names to extract or create from file FILE NAME.

   If you give a single dash as a file name for @{b}--files-from@{ub}, (i.e.,
you specify either @{b}--files-from=-@{ub} or @{b}-T -@{ub}), then the file names are
read from standard input.

   Unless you are running @{b}tar@{ub} with @{b}--create@{ub}, you can not use both
@{b}--files-from=-@{ub} and @{b}--file=-@{ub} (@{b}-f -@{ub}) in the same command.

   The following example shows how to use @{b}find@{ub} to generate a list of
files smaller than 400K in length and put that list into a file called
@{b}small-files@{ub}.  You can then use the @{b}-T@{ub} option to @{b}tar@{ub} to specify the
files from that file, @{b}small-files@{ub}, to create the archive @{b}little.tgz@{ub}.
(The @{b}-z@{ub} option to @{b}tar@{ub} compresses the archive with @{b}gzip@{ub}; see @{"gzip" link "gzip"} for
more information.)

     $ find . -size -400 -print > small-files
     $ tar -c -v -z -T small-files -f little.tgz


 @{" nul " link "nul"}


@endnode

@node "nul" "tar.guide/nul"
@prev "files"
@toc "files"

@{b}NUL@{ub} Terminated File Names
-------------------------

   The @{b}--null@{ub} option causes @{b}--files-from=FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub} (@{b}-T
FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub}) to read file names terminated by a @{b}NUL@{ub} instead of a
newline, so files whose names contain newlines can be archived using
@{b}--files-from@{ub}.

@{b}--null@{ub}
     Only consider @{b}NUL@{ub} terminated file names, instead of files that
     terminate in a newline.

   The @{b}--null@{ub} option is just like the one in GNU @{b}xargs@{ub} and @{b}cpio@{ub}, and is
useful with the @{b}-print0@{ub} predicate of GNU @{b}find@{ub}.  In @{b}tar@{ub}, @{b}--null@{ub} also
causes @{b}--directory=DIRECTORY@{ub} (@{b}-C DIRECTORY@{ub}) options to be treated as
file names to archive, in case there are any files out there called @{b}-C@{ub}.

   This example shows how to use @{b}find@{ub} to generate a list of files
larger than 800K in length and put that list into a file called
@{b}long-files@{ub}.  The @{b}-print0@{ub} option to @{b}find@{ub} just just like @{b}-print@{ub}, except
that it separates files with a @{b}NUL@{ub} rather than with a newline.  You can
then run @{b}tar@{ub} with both the @{b}--null@{ub} and @{b}-T@{ub} options to specify that @{b}tar@{ub}
get the files from that file, @{b}long-files@{ub}, to create the archive
@{b}big.tgz@{ub}.  The @{b}--null@{ub} option to @{b}tar@{ub} will cause @{b}tar@{ub} to recognize the @{b}NUL@{ub}
separator between files.

     $ find . -size +800 -print0 > long-files
     $ tar -c -v --null --files-from=long-files --file=big.tar


@endnode

@node "exclude" "tar.guide/exclude"
@next "Wildcards"
@prev "files"
@toc "Choosing"

Excluding Some Files
====================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   To avoid operating on files whose names match a particular pattern,
use the @{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub} or @{b}--exclude-from=FILE-OF-PATTERNS@{ub} (@{b}-X
FILE-OF-PATTERNS@{ub}) options.

@{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub}
     Causes @{b}tar@{ub} to ignore files that match the PATTERN.

   The @{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub} option will prevent any file or member which
matches the shell wildcards (PATTERN) from being operated on (PATTERN
can be a single file name or a more complex expression).  For example,
if you want to create an archive with all the contents of @{b}/tmp@{ub} except
the file @{b}/tmp/foo@{ub}, you can use the command @{b}tar --create --file=arch.tar
--exclude=foo@{ub}.  You may give multiple @{b}--exclude@{ub} options.

@{b}--exclude-from=FILE@{ub}
@{b}-X FILE@{ub}
     Causes @{b}tar@{ub} to ignore files that match the patterns listed in FILE.

   Use the @{b}--exclude-from=FILE-OF-PATTERNS@{ub} option to read a list of
shell wildcards, one per line, from FILE; @{b}tar@{ub} will ignore files
matching those regular expressions.  Thus if @{b}tar@{ub} is called as
@{b}tar -c -X foo .@{ub} and the file @{b}foo@{ub} contains a single line @{b}*.o@{ub}, no files
whose names end in @{b}.o@{ub} will be added to the archive.


 @{" problems with exclude " link "problems with exclude"}


@endnode

@node "problems with exclude" "tar.guide/problems with exclude"
@prev "exclude"
@toc "exclude"

Problems with Using the @{b}exclude@{ub} Options
---------------------------------------

   Some users find @{b}exclude@{ub} options confusing.  Here are some common
pitfalls:

   * The main operating mode of @{b}tar@{ub} will always act on file names
     listed on the command line, no matter whether or not there is an
     exclusion which would otherwise affect them.  In the example
     above, if you create an archive and exclude files that end with
     @{b}*.o@{ub}, but explicitly name the file @{b}catc.o@{ub} after all the options
     have been listed, @{b}catc.o@{ub} @{i}will@{ui} be included in the archive.

   * You can sometimes confuse the meanings of @{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub} and
     @{b}--exclude-from=FILE-OF-PATTERNS@{ub} (@{b}-X FILE-OF-PATTERNS@{ub}).  Be
     careful: use @{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub} when files to be excluded are given
     as a pattern on the command line.  Use
     @{b}--exclude-from=FILE-OF-PATTERNS@{ub} to introduce the name of a file
     which contains a list of patterns, one per line; each of these
     patterns can exclude zero, one, or many files.

   * When you use @{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub}, be sure to quote the PATTERN
     parameter, so GNU @{b}tar@{ub} sees wildcard characters like @{b}*@{ub}.  If you do
     not do this, the shell might expand the @{b}*@{ub} itself using files at
     hand, so @{b}tar@{ub} might receive a list of files instead of one pattern,
     or none at all, making the command somewhat illegal.  This might
     not correspond to what you want.

     For example, write:

          $ tar -c -f ARCHIVE.TAR -X '*/tmp/*' DIRECTORY

     rather than:

          $ tar -c -f ARCHIVE.TAR -X */tmp/* DIRECTORY

   * You must use use shell syntax, or globbing, rather than @{b}regexp@{ub}
     syntax, when using exclude options in @{b}tar@{ub}.  If you try to use
     @{b}regexp@{ub} syntax to describe files to be excluded, your command might
     fail.

   * In earlier versions of @{b}tar@{ub}, what is now the
     @{b}--exclude-from=FILE-OF-PATTERNS@{ub} option was called
     @{b}--exclude-PATTERN@{ub} instead.  Now, @{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub} applies to
     patterns listed on the command line and
     @{b}--exclude-from=FILE-OF-PATTERNS@{ub} applies to patterns listed in a
     file.


@endnode

@node "Wildcards" "tar.guide/Wildcards"
@next "after"
@prev "exclude"
@toc "Choosing"

Wildcards Patterns and Matching
===============================

@{i}   Globbing@{ui} is the operation by which @{i}wildcard@{ui} characters, @{b}*@{ub} or @{b}?@{ub} for
example, are replaced and expanded into all existing files matching the
given pattern.  However, @{b}tar@{ub} often uses wildcard patterns for matching
(or globbing) archive members instead of actual files in the
filesystem.  Wildcard patterns are also used for verifying volume
labels of @{b}tar@{ub} archives.  This section has the purpose of explaining
wildcard syntax for @{b}tar@{ub}.

   A PATTERN should be written according to shell syntax, using wildcard
characters to effect globbing.  Most characters in the pattern stand
for themselves in the matched string, and case is significant: @{b}a@{ub} will
match only @{b}a@{ub}, and not @{b}A@{ub}.  The character @{b}?@{ub} in the pattern matches any
single character in the matched string.  The character @{b}*@{ub} in the pattern
matches zero, one, or more single characters in the matched string.
The character @{b}\\ @{ub} says to take the following character of the pattern
@{i}literally@{ui}; it is useful when one needs to match the @{b}?@{ub}, @{b}*@{ub}, @{b}[@{ub} or @{b}\\ @{ub}
characters, themselves.

   The character @{b}[@{ub}, up to the matching @{b}]@{ub}, introduces a character class.
A @{i}character class@{ui} is a list of acceptable characters for the next
single character of the matched string.  For example, @{b}[abcde]@{ub} would
match any of the first five letters of the alphabet.  Note that within
a character class, all of the "special characters" listed above other
than @{b}\\ @{ub} lose their special meaning; for example, @{b}[-\\\\[*?]]@{ub} would
match any of the characters, @{b}-@{ub}, @{b}\\ @{ub}, @{b}[@{ub}, @{b}*@{ub}, @{b}?@{ub}, or @{b}]@{ub}.  (Due to parsing
constraints, the characters @{b}-@{ub} and @{b}]@{ub} must either come @{i}first@{ui} or @{i}last@{ui} in a
character class.)

   If the first character of the class after the opening @{b}[@{ub} is @{b}!@{ub} or @{b}^@{ub},
then the meaning of the class is reversed.  Rather than listing
character to match, it lists those characters which are @{i}forbidden@{ui} as
the next single character of the matched string.

   Other characters of the class stand for themselves.  The special
construction @{b}[A-E]@{ub}, using an hyphen between two letters, is meant to
represent all characters between A and E, inclusive.

   Periods (@{b}.@{ub}) or forward slashes (@{b}/@{ub}) are not considered special for
wildcard matches.  However, if a pattern completely matches a directory
prefix of a matched string, then it matches the full matched string:
excluding a directory also excludes all the files beneath it.

   There are some discussions floating in the air and asking for
modifications in the way GNU @{b}tar@{ub} accomplishes wildcard matches.  We
perceive any change of semantics in this area as a delicate thing to
impose on GNU @{b}tar@{ub} users.  On the other hand, the GNU project should be
progressive enough to correct any ill design: compatibility at all price
is not always a good attitude.  In conclusion, it is @{i}possible@{ui} that
slight amendments be later brought to the previous description.  Your
opinions on the matter are welcome.


@endnode

@node "after" "tar.guide/after"
@next "recurse"
@prev "Wildcards"
@toc "Choosing"

Operating Only on New Files
===========================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   The @{b}--after-date=DATE@{ub} (@{b}--newer=DATE@{ub}, @{b}-N DATE@{ub}) option causes @{b}tar@{ub} to
only work on files whose modification or inode-changed times are newer
than the DATE given.  If you use this option when creating or appending
to an archive, the archive will only include new files.  If you use
@{b}--after-date@{ub} when extracting an archive, @{b}tar@{ub} will only extract files
newer than the DATE you specify.

   If you only want @{b}tar@{ub} to make the date comparison based on
modification of the actual contents of the file (rather than inode
changes), then use the @{b}--newer-mtime=DATE@{ub} option.

   You may use these options with any operation.  Note that these
options differ from the @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}) operation in that they allow you
to specify a particular date against which @{b}tar@{ub} can compare when
deciding whether or not to archive the files.

@{b}--after-date=DATE@{ub}
@{b}--newer=DATE@{ub}
@{b}-N DATE@{ub}
     Only store files newer than DATE.

     Acts on files only if their modification or inode-changed times are
     later than DATE.  Use in conjunction with any operation.

@{b}--newer-mtime=DATE@{ub}
     Acts like @{b}--after-date=DATE@{ub} (@{b}--newer=DATE@{ub}, @{b}-N DATE@{ub}), but only
     looks at modification times.

   These options limit @{b}tar@{ub} to only operating on files which have been
modified after the date specified.  A file is considered to have
changed if the contents have been modified, or if the owner,
permissions, and so forth, have been changed.  (For more information on
how to specify a date, see @{"Date input formats" link "Date input formats"}; remember that the
entire date argument must be quoted if it contains any spaces.)

   Gurus would say that @{b}--after-date=DATE@{ub} (@{b}--newer=DATE@{ub}, @{b}-N DATE@{ub}) tests
both the @{b}mtime@{ub} (time the contents of the file were last modified) and
@{b}ctime@{ub} (time the file's status was last changed: owner, permissions, etc)
fields, while @{b}--newer-mtime=DATE@{ub} tests only @{b}mtime@{ub} field.

   To be precise, @{b}--after-date=DATE@{ub} (@{b}--newer=DATE@{ub}, @{b}-N DATE@{ub}) checks @{i}both@{ui}
@{b}mtime@{ub} and @{b}ctime@{ub} and processes the file if either one is more recent than
DATE, while @{b}--newer-mtime=DATE@{ub} only checks @{b}mtime@{ub} and disregards @{b}ctime@{ub}.
Neither uses @{b}atime@{ub} (the last time the contents of the file were looked
at).

   Date specifiers can have embedded spaces.  Because of this, you may
need to quote date arguments to keep the shell from parsing them as
separate arguments.

@{b}     Please Note:@{ub} @{b}--after-date=DATE@{ub} (@{b}--newer=DATE@{ub}, @{b}-N DATE@{ub}) and
     @{b}--newer-mtime=DATE@{ub} should not be used for incremental backups.
     Some files (such as those in renamed directories) are not selected
     properly by these options.  See
     @{"incremental and listed-incremental" link "incremental and listed-incremental"}.

   To select files newer than the modification time of a file that
already exists, you can use the @{b}--reference@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}) option of GNU @{b}date@{ub},
available in GNU shell utilities 1.13 or later.  It returns the
timestamp of that already existing file; this timestamp expands to
become the referent date which @{b}--newer@{ub} uses to determine which files to
archive.  For example, you could say,

     $ tar -cf ARCHIVE.TAR --newer="`date -r FILE`" /home

which tells .


@endnode

@node "recurse" "tar.guide/recurse"
@next "one"
@prev "after"
@toc "Choosing"

Descending into Directories
===========================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   Usually, @{b}tar@{ub} will recursively explore all directories (either those
given on the command line or through the @{b}--files-from=FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub} (@{b}-T
FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub}) option) for the various files they contain.  However,
you may not always want @{b}tar@{ub} to act this way.

   The @{b}--no-recursion@{ub} option inhibits @{b}tar@{ub}'s recursive descent into
specified directories.  If you specify @{b}--no-recursion@{ub}, you can use the
@{b}find@{ub} utility for hunting through levels of directories to construct a
list of file names which you could then pass to @{b}tar@{ub}.  @{b}find@{ub} allows you
to be more selective when choosing which files to archive; see @{"files" link "files"}
for more information on using @{b}find@{ub} with @{b}tar@{ub}, or look.

@{b}--no-recursion@{ub}
     Prevents @{b}tar@{ub} from recursively descending directories.

   When you use @{b}--no-recursion@{ub}, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} grabs directory entries
themselves, but does not descend on them recursively.  Many people use
@{b}find@{ub} for locating files they want to back up, and since @{b}tar@{ub} @{i}usually@{ui}
recursively descends on directories, they have to use the @{b}! -d@{ub} option
to @{b}find@{ub}  as they usually do not want all the files in a directory.
They then use the {No Value For "op-file-from"} option to archive the
files located via @{b}find@{ub}.

   The problem when restoring files archived in this manner is that the
directories themselves are not in the archive; so the
@{b}--same-permissions@{ub} (@{b}--preserve-permissions@{ub}, @{b}-p@{ub}) option does not affect
them--while users might really like it to.  Specifying @{b}--no-recursion@{ub}
is a way to tell @{b}tar@{ub} to grab only the directory entries given to it,
adding no new files on its own.


@endnode

@node "one" "tar.guide/one"
@prev "recurse"
@toc "Choosing"

Crossing Filesystem Boundaries
==============================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

@{b}   tar@{ub} will normally automatically cross file system boundaries in
order to archive files which are part of a directory tree.  You can
change this behavior by running @{b}tar@{ub} and specifying @{b}--one-file-system@{ub}
(@{b}-l@{ub}).  This option only affects files that are archived because they
are in a directory that is being archived; @{b}tar@{ub} will still archive files
explicitly named on the command line or through
@{b}--files-from=FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub} (@{b}-T FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub}), regardless of where they
reside.

@{b}--one-file-system@{ub}
@{b}-l@{ub}
     Prevents @{b}tar@{ub} from crossing file system boundaries when archiving.
     Use in conjunction with any write operation.

   The @{b}--one-file-system@{ub} option causes @{b}tar@{ub} to modify its normal
behavior in archiving the contents of directories.  If a file in a
directory is not on the same filesystem as the directory itself, then
@{b}tar@{ub} will not archive that file.  If the file is a directory itself, @{b}tar@{ub}
will not archive anything beneath it; in other words, @{b}tar@{ub} will not
cross mount points.

   It is reported that using this option, the mount point is is
archived, but nothing under it.

   This option is useful for making full or incremental archival
backups of a file system.  If this option is used in conjunction with
@{b}--verbose@{ub} (@{b}-v@{ub}), files that are excluded are mentioned by name on the
standard error.


 @{" directory                  " link "directory"}  Changing Directory
 @{" absolute                   " link "absolute"}  Absolute File Names


@endnode

@node "directory" "tar.guide/directory"
@next "absolute"
@prev "one"
@toc "one"

Changing the Working Directory
------------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   To change the working directory in the middle of a list of file
names, either on the command line or in a file specified using
@{b}--files-from=FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub} (@{b}-T FILE-OF-NAMES@{ub}), use
@{b}--directory=DIRECTORY@{ub} (@{b}-C DIRECTORY@{ub}).  This will change the working
directory to the directory DIRECTORY after that point in the list.

@{b}--directory=DIRECTORY@{ub}
@{b}-C DIRECTORY@{ub}
     Changes the working directory in the middle of a command line.

   For example,

     $ tar -c -f jams.tar grape prune -C food cherry

will place the files @{b}grape@{ub} and @{b}prune@{ub} from the current directory into
the archive @{b}jams.tar@{ub}, followed by the file @{b}cherry@{ub} from the directory
@{b}food@{ub}.  This option is especially useful when you have several widely
separated files that you want to store in the same archive.

   Note that the file @{b}cherry@{ub} is recorded in the archive under the
precise name @{b}cherry@{ub}, @{i}not@{ui} @{b}food/cherry@{ub}.  Thus, the archive will contain
three files that all appear to have come from the same directory; if
the archive is extracted with plain @{b}tar --extract@{ub}, all three files will
be written in the current directory.

   Contrast this with the command,

     $ tar -c -f jams.tar grape prune -C food red/cherry

which records the third file in the archive under the name @{b}red/cherry@{ub}
so that, if the archive is extracted using @{b}tar --extract@{ub}, the third
file will be written in a subdirectory named @{b}orange-colored@{ub}.

   You can use the @{b}--directory@{ub} option to make the archive independent
of the original name of the directory holding the files.  The following
command places the files @{b}/etc/passwd@{ub}, @{b}/etc/hosts@{ub}, and @{b}/lib/libc.a@{ub} into
the archive @{b}foo.tar@{ub}:

     $ tar -c -f foo.tar -C /etc passwd hosts -C /lib libc.a

However, the names of the archive members will be exactly what they were
on the command line: @{b}passwd@{ub}, @{b}hosts@{ub}, and @{b}libc.a@{ub}.  They will not appear
to be related by file name to the original directories where those
files were located.

   Note that @{b}--directory@{ub} options are interpreted consecutively.  If
@{b}--directory@{ub} specifies a relative file name, it is interpreted relative
to the then current directory, which might not be the same as the
original current working directory of @{b}tar@{ub}, due to a previous
@{b}--directory@{ub} option.

   When using @{b}--files-from@{ub} (see @{"files" link "files"}), you can put @{b}-C@{ub} options in the
file list.  Unfortunately, you cannot put @{b}--directory@{ub} options in the
file list.  (This interpretation can be disabled by using the @{b}--null@{ub}
option.)


@endnode

@node "absolute" "tar.guide/absolute"
@prev "directory"
@toc "one"

Absolute File Names
-------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

@{b}-P@{ub}
@{b}--absolute-names@{ub}
     Do not strip leading slashes from file names.

   By default, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} drops a leading @{b}/@{ub} on input or output.  This
option turns off this behavior; it is equivalent to changing to the
root directory before running @{b}tar@{ub} (except it also turns off the usual
warning message).

   When @{b}tar@{ub} extracts archive members from an archive, it strips any
leading slashes (@{b}/@{ub}) from the member name.  This causes absolute member
names in the archive to be treated as relative file names.  This allows
you to have such members extracted wherever you want, instead of being
restricted to extracting the member in the exact directory named in the
archive.  For example, if the archive member has the name @{b}/etc/passwd@{ub},
@{b}tar@{ub} will extract it as if the name were really @{b}etc/passwd@{ub}.

   Other @{b}tar@{ub} programs do not do this.  As a result, if you create an
archive whose member names start with a slash, they will be difficult
for other people with a non-GNU @{b}tar@{ub} program to use.  Therefore, GNU @{b}tar@{ub}
also strips leading slashes from member names when putting members into
the archive.  For example, if you ask @{b}tar@{ub} to add the file @{b}/bin/ls@{ub} to an
archive, it will do so, but the member name will be @{b}bin/ls@{ub}.

   If you use the @{b}--absolute-names@{ub} (@{b}-P@{ub}) option, @{b}tar@{ub} will do neither of
these transformations.

   To archive or extract files relative to the root directory, specify
the @{b}--absolute-names@{ub} (@{b}-P@{ub}) option.

   Normally, @{b}tar@{ub} acts on files relative to the working
directory--ignoring superior directory names when archiving, and
ignoring leading slashes when extracting.

   When you specify @{b}--absolute-names@{ub} (@{b}-P@{ub}), @{b}tar@{ub} stores file names
including all superior directory names, and preserves leading slashes.
If you only invoked @{b}tar@{ub} from the root directory you would never need
the @{b}--absolute-names@{ub} (@{b}-P@{ub}) option, but using this option may be more
convenient than switching to root.

@{b}--absolute-names@{ub}
     Preserves full file names (inclusing superior dirctory names) when
     archiving files.  Preserves leading slash when extracting files.

@{b}   tar@{ub} prints out a message about removing the @{b}/@{ub} from file names.  This
message appears once per GNU @{b}tar@{ub} invocation.  It represents something
which ought to be told; ignoring what it means can cause very serious
surprises, later.

   Some people, nevertheless, do not want to see this message.  Wanting
to play really dangerously, one may of course redirect @{b}tar@{ub} standard
error to the sink.  For example, under @{b}sh@{ub}:

     $ tar -c -f archive.tar /home 2> /dev/null

Another solution, both nicer and simpler, would be to change to the @{b}/@{ub}
directory first, and then avoid absolute notation.  For example:

     $ (cd / && tar -c -f archive.tar home)
     $ tar -c -f archive.tar -C  / home


@endnode

@node "Date input formats" "tar.guide/Date input formats"
@next "Formats"
@prev "Choosing"
@toc "Main"

Date input formats
******************

     Our units of temporal measurement, from seconds on up to months,
     are so complicated, asymmetrical and disjunctive so as to make
     coherent mental reckoning in time all but impossible.  Indeed, had
     some tyrannical god contrived to enslave our minds to time, to
     make it all but impossible for us to escape subjection to sodden
     routines and unpleasant surprises, he could hardly have done
     better than handing down our present system.  It is like a set of
     trapezoidal building blocks, with no vertical or horizontal
     surfaces, like a language in which the simplest thought demands
     ornate constructions, useless particles and lengthy
     circumlocutions.  Unlike the more successful patterns of language
     and science, which enable us to face experience boldly or at least
     level-headedly, our system of temporal calculation silently and
     persistently encourages our terror of time.

     ...  It is as though architects had to measure length in feet,
     width in meters and height in ells; as though basic instruction
     manuals demanded a knowledge of five different languages.  It is
     no wonder then that we often look into our own immediate past or
     future, last Tuesday or a week from Sunday, with feelings of
     helpless confusion.  ...

     -- Robert Grudin, `Time and the Art of Living'.

   This section describes the textual date representations that GNU
programs accept.  These are the strings you, as a user, can supply as
arguments to the various programs.  The C interface (via the @{b}getdate@{ub}
function) is not described here.

   Although the date syntax here can represent any possible time since
zero A.D., computer integers are not big enough for such a
(comparatively) long time.  The earliest date semantically allowed on
Unix systems is midnight, 1 January 1970 UCT.


 @{" General date syntax        " link "General date syntax"}  Common rules.
 @{" Calendar date item         " link "Calendar date item"}  19 Dec 1994.
 @{" Time of day item           " link "Time of day item"}  9:20pm.
 @{" Timezone item              " link "Timezone item"}  EST, DST, BST, UCT, AHST, ...
 @{" Day of week item           " link "Day of week item"}  Monday and others.
 @{" Relative item in date strings " link "Relative item in date strings"}  next tuesday, 2 years ago.
 @{" Pure numbers in date strings " link "Pure numbers in date strings"}  19931219, 1440.
 @{" Authors of getdate         " link "Authors of getdate"}  Bellovin, Salz, Berets, et al.


@endnode

@node "General date syntax" "tar.guide/General date syntax"
@next "Calendar date item"
@prev "Date input formats"
@toc "Date input formats"

General date syntax
===================

   A @{i}date@{ui} is a string, possibly empty, containing many items separated
by whitespace.  The whitespace may be omitted when no ambiguity arises.
The empty string means the beginning of today (i.e., midnight).  Order
of the items is immaterial.  A date string may contain many flavors of
items:

   * calendar date items

   * time of the day items

   * time zone items

   * day of the week items

   * relative items

   * pure numbers.

We describe each of these item types in turn, below.

   A few numbers may be written out in words in most contexts.  This is
most useful for specifying day of the week items or relative items (see
below).  Here is the list: @{b}first@{ub} for 1, @{b}next@{ub} for 2, @{b}third@{ub} for 3, @{b}fourth@{ub}
for 4, @{b}fifth@{ub} for 5, @{b}sixth@{ub} for 6, @{b}seventh@{ub} for 7, @{b}eighth@{ub} for 8, @{b}ninth@{ub} for
9, @{b}tenth@{ub} for 10, @{b}eleventh@{ub} for 11 and @{b}twelfth@{ub} for 12.  Also, @{b}last@{ub} means
exactly -1.

   When a month is written this way, it is still considered to be
written numerically, instead of being "spelled in full"; this changes
the allowed strings.

   Alphabetic case is completely ignored in dates.  Comments may be
introduced between round parentheses, as long as included parentheses
are properly nested.  Hyphens not followed by a digit are currently
ignored.  Leading zeros on numbers are ignored.


@endnode

@node "Calendar date item" "tar.guide/Calendar date item"
@next "Time of day item"
@prev "General date syntax"
@toc "Date input formats"

Calendar date item
==================

   A @{i}calendar date item@{ui} specifies a day of the year.  It is specified
differently, depending on whether the month is specified numerically or
literally.  All these strings specify the same calendar date:

     1970-09-17           # ISO 8601.
     70-9-17              # This century assumed by default.
     70-09-17             # Leading zeros are ignored.
     9/17/72              # Common U.S. writing.
     24 September 1972
     24 Sept 72           # September has a special abbreviation.
     24 Sep 72            # Three-letter abbreviations always allowed.
     Sep 24, 1972
     24-sep-72
     24sep72

   The year can also be omitted.  In this case, the last specified year
is used, or the current year if none.  For example:

     9/17
     sep 17

   Here are the rules.

   For numeric months, the ISO 8601 format @{b}YEAR-MONTH-DAY@{ub} is allowed,
where YEAR is any positive number, MONTH is a number between 01 and 12,
and DAY is a number between 01 and 31.  A leading zero must be present
if a number is less than ten.  If YEAR is less than 100, then 1900 is
added to it to force a date in this century.  The construct
@{b}MONTH/DAY/YEAR@{ub}, popular in the United States, is accepted.  Also
@{b}MONTH/DAY@{ub}, omitting the year.

   Literal months may be spelled out in full: @{b}January@{ub}, @{b}February@{ub}, @{b}March@{ub},
@{b}April@{ub}, @{b}May@{ub}, @{b}June@{ub}, @{b}July@{ub}, @{b}August@{ub}, @{b}September@{ub}, @{b}October@{ub}, @{b}November@{ub} or
@{b}December@{ub}.  Literal months may be abbreviated to their first three
letters, possibly followed by an abbreviating dot.  It is also
permitted to write @{b}Sept@{ub} instead of @{b}September@{ub}.

   When months are written literally, the calendar date may be given as
any of the following:

     DAY MONTH YEAR
     DAY MONTH
     MONTH DAY YEAR
     DAY-MONTH-YEAR

   Or, omitting the year:

     MONTH DAY


@endnode

@node "Time of day item" "tar.guide/Time of day item"
@next "Timezone item"
@prev "Calendar date item"
@toc "Date input formats"

Time of day item
================

   A @{i}time of day item@{ui} in date strings specifies the time on a given
day.  Here are some examples, all of which represent the same time:

     20:02:0
     20:02
     8:02pm
     20:02-0500      # In EST (Eastern U.S. Standard Time).

   More generally, the time of the day may be given as
@{b}HOUR:MINUTE:SECOND@{ub}, where HOUR is a number between 0 and 23, MINUTE is
a number between 0 and 59, and SECOND is a number between 0 and 59.
Alternatively, @{b}:SECOND@{ub} can be omitted, in which case it is taken to be
zero.

   If the time is followed by @{b}am@{ub} or @{b}pm@{ub} (or @{b}a.m.@{ub} or @{b}p.m.@{ub}), HOUR is
restricted to run from 1 to 12, and @{b}:MINUTE@{ub} may be omitted (taken to be
zero).  @{b}am@{ub} indicates the first half of the day, @{b}pm@{ub} indicates the second
half of the day.  In this notation, 12 is the predecessor of 1:
midnight is @{b}12am@{ub} while noon is @{b}12pm@{ub}.

   The time may alternatively be followed by a timezone correction,
expressed as @{b}SHHMM@{ub}, where S is @{b}+@{ub} or @{b}-@{ub}, HH is a number of zone hours and
MM is a number of zone minutes.  When a timezone correction is given
this way, it forces interpretation of the time in UTC, overriding any
previous specification for the timezone or the local timezone.  The
MINUTE part of the time of the day may not be elided when a timezone
correction is used.  This is the only way to specify a timezone
correction by fractional parts of an hour.

   Either @{b}am@{ub}/@{b}pm@{ub} or a timezone correction may be specified, but not both.


@endnode

@node "Timezone item" "tar.guide/Timezone item"
@next "Day of week item"
@prev "Time of day item"
@toc "Date input formats"

Timezone item
=============

   A @{i}timezone item@{ui} specifies an international timezone, indicated by a
small set of letters.  Any included period is ignored.  Military
timezone designations use a single letter.  Currently, only integral
zone hours may be represented in a timezone item.  See the previous
section for a finer control over the timezone correction.

   Here are many non-daylight-savings-time timezones, indexed by the
zone hour value.

+000
