@node "Portability" "tar.guide/Portability"
@next "Compression"
@prev "Formats"
@toc "Formats"

Making @{b}tar@{ub} Archives More Portable
=================================

   Creating a @{b}tar@{ub} archive on a particular system that is meant to be
useful later on many other machines and with other versions of @{b}tar@{ub} is
more challenging than you might think.  @{b}tar@{ub} archive formats have been
evolving since the first versions of Unix.  Many such formats are
around, and are not always comptible with each other.  This section
discusses a few problems, and gives some advice about making @{b}tar@{ub}
archives more portable.

   One golden rule is simplicity.  For example, limit your @{b}tar@{ub} archives
to contain only regular files and directories, avoiding other kind of
special files.  Do not attempt to save sparse files or contiguous files
as such.  Let's discuss a few more problems, in turn.


 @{" Portable Names             " link "Portable Names"}  Portable Names
 @{" dereference                " link "dereference"}  Symbolic Links
 @{" old                        " link "old"}  Old V7 Archives
 @{" posix                      " link "posix"}  POSIX archives
 @{" Checksumming               " link "Checksumming"}  Checksumming Problems


@endnode

@node "Portable Names" "tar.guide/Portable Names"
@next "dereference"
@prev "Portability"
@toc "Portability"

Portable Names
--------------

   Use @{i}straight@{ui} file and directory names, made up of printable ASCII
characters, avoiding colons, slashes, backslashes, spaces, and other
@{i}dangerous@{ui} characters.  Avoid deep directory nesting.  Accounting for
oldish System V machines, limit your file and directory names to 14
characters or less.

   If you intend to have your @{b}tar@{ub} archives to be read under MSDOS, you
should not rely on case distinction for file names, and you might use
the GNU @{b}doschk@{ub} program for helping you further diagnosing illegal MSDOS
names, which are even more limited than System V's.


@endnode

@node "dereference" "tar.guide/dereference"
@next "old"
@prev "Portable Names"
@toc "Portability"

Symbolic Links
--------------

   Normally, when @{b}tar@{ub} archives a symbolic link, it writes a block to
the archive naming the target of the link.  In that way, the @{b}tar@{ub}
archive is a faithful record of the filesystem contents.  @{b}--dereference@{ub}
(@{b}-h@{ub}) is used with @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}), and causes @{b}tar@{ub} to archive the files
symbolic links point to, instead of the links themselves.  When this
option is used, when @{b}tar@{ub} encounters a symbolic link, it will archive
the linked-to file, instead of simply recording the presence of a
symbolic link.

   The name under which the file is stored in the file system is not
recorded in the archive.  To record both the symbolic link name and the
file name in the system, archive the file under both names.  If all
links were recorded automatically by @{b}tar@{ub}, an extracted file might be
linked to a file name that no longer exists in the file system.

   If a linked-to file is encountered again by @{b}tar@{ub} while creating the
same archive, an entire second copy of it will be stored.  (This @{i}might@{ui}
be considered a bug.)

   So, for portable archives, do not archive symbolic links as such,
and use @{b}--dereference@{ub} (@{b}-h@{ub}): many systems do not support symbolic links,
and moreover, your distribution might be unusable if it contains
unresolved symbolic links.


@endnode

@node "old" "tar.guide/old"
@next "posix"
@prev "dereference"
@toc "Portability"

Old V7 Archives
---------------

   Certain old versions of @{b}tar@{ub} cannot handle additional information
recorded by newer @{b}tar@{ub} programs.  To create an archive in V7 format (not
ANSI), which can be read by these old versions, specify the
@{b}--old-archive@{ub} (@{b}-o@{ub}) option in conjunction with the @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}).  @{b}tar@{ub}
also accepts @{b}--portability@{ub} for this option.  When you specify it, @{b}tar@{ub}
leaves out information about directories, pipes, fifos, contiguous
files, and device files, and specifies file ownership by group and user
IDs instead of group and user names.

   When updating an archive, do not use @{b}--old-archive@{ub} (@{b}-o@{ub}) unless the
archive was created with using this option.

   In most cases, a @{i}new@{ui} format archive can be read by an @{i}old@{ui} @{b}tar@{ub}
program without serious trouble, so this option should seldom be
needed.  On the other hand, most modern @{b}tar@{ub}s are able to read old
format archives, so it might be safer for you to always use
@{b}--old-archive@{ub} (@{b}-o@{ub}) for your distributions.


@endnode

@node "posix" "tar.guide/posix"
@next "Checksumming"
@prev "old"
@toc "Portability"

GNU @{b}tar@{ub} and POSIX @{b}tar@{ub}
---------------------

   GNU @{b}tar@{ub} was based on an early draft of the POSIX 1003.1 @{b}ustar@{ub}
standard.  GNU extensions to @{b}tar@{ub}, such as the support for file names
longer than 100 characters, use portions of the @{b}tar@{ub} header record which
were specified in that POSIX draft as unused.  Subsequent changes in
POSIX have allocated the same parts of the header record for other
purposes.  As a result, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} is incompatible with the current POSIX
spec, and with @{b}tar@{ub} programs that follow it.

   We plan to reimplement these GNU extensions in a new way which is
upward compatible with the latest POSIX @{b}tar@{ub} format, but we don't know
when this will be done.

   In the mean time, there is simply no telling what might happen if you
read a GNU @{b}tar@{ub} archive, which uses the GNU extensions, using some other
@{b}tar@{ub} program.  So if you want to read the archive with another @{b}tar@{ub}
program, be sure to write it using the @{b}--old-archive@{ub} option (@{b}-o@{ub}).

   Traditionally, old @{b}tar@{ub}s have a limit of 100 characters.  GNU @{b}tar@{ub}
attempted two different approaches to overcome this limit, using and
extending a format specified by a draft of some P1003.1.  The first way
was not that successful, and involved @{b}\@MaNgLeD@@{ub} file names, or such;
while a second approach used @{b}././@LongLink@{ub} and other tricks, yielding
better success.  In theory, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} should be able to handle file names
of practically unlimited length.  So, if GNU @{b}tar@{ub} fails to dump and
retrieve files having more than 100 characters, then there is a bug in
GNU @{b}tar@{ub}, indeed.

   But, being strictly POSIX, the limit was still 100 characters.  For
various other purposes, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} used areas left unassigned in the POSIX
draft.  POSIX later revised P1003.1 @{b}ustar@{ub} format by assigning
previously unused header fields, in such a way that the upper limit for
file name length was raised to 256 characters.  However, the actual
POSIX limit oscillates between 100 and 256, depending on the precise
location of slashes in full file name (this is rather ugly).  Since GNU
@{b}tar@{ub} use the same fields for quite other purposes, it became
incompatible with the latest POSIX standards.

   For longer or non-fitting file names, we plan to use yet another set
of GNU extensions, but this time, complying with the provisions POSIX
offers for extending the format, rather than conflicting with it.
Whenever an archive uses old GNU @{b}tar@{ub} extension format or POSIX
extensions, would it be for very long file names or other specialities,
this archive becomes non-portable to other @{b}tar@{ub} implementations.  In
fact, anything can happen.  The most forgiving @{b}tar@{ub}s will merely unpack
the file using a wrong name, and maybe create another file named
something like @{b}\@LongName@{ub}, with the true file name in it.  @{b}tar@{ub}s not
protecting themselves may segment violate!

   Compatibility concerns make all this thing more difficult, as we
will have to support @{i}all@{ui} these things together, for a while.  GNU @{b}tar@{ub}
should be able to produce and read true POSIX format files, while being
able to detect old GNU @{b}tar@{ub} formats, besides old V7 format, and process
them conveniently.  It would take years before this whole area
stabilizes...

   There are plans to raise this 100 limit to 256, and yet produce POSIX
conformant archives.  Past 256, I do not know yet if GNU @{b}tar@{ub} will go
non-POSIX again, or merely refuse to archive the file.

   There are plans so GNU @{b}tar@{ub} support more fully the latest POSIX
format, while being able to read old V7 format, GNU (semi-POSIX plus
extension), as well as full POSIX.  One may ask if there is part of the
POSIX format that we still cannot support.  This simple question has a
complex answer.  Maybe that, on intimate look, some strong limitations
will pop up, but until now, nothing sounds too difficult (but see
below).  I only have these few pages of POSIX telling about `Extended
tar Format' (P1003.1-1990 - section 10.1.1), and there are references
to other parts of the standard I do not have, which should normally
enforce limitations on stored file names (I suspect things like fixing
what @{b}/@{ub} and @{b}<NUL>@{ub} means).  There are also some points which the standard
does not make clear, Existing practice will then drive what I should do.

   POSIX mandates that, when a file name cannot fit within 100 to 256
characters (the variance comes from the fact a @{b}/@{ub} is ideally needed as
the 156'th character), or a link name cannot fit within 100 characters,
a warning should be issued and the file @{i}not@{ui} be stored.  Unless some
@{b}--posix@{ub} option is given (or @{b}POSIXLY_CORRECT@{ub} is set), I suspect that GNU
@{b}tar@{ub} should disobey this specification, and automatically switch to using
GNU extensions to overcome file name or link name length limitations.

   There is a problem, however, which I did not intimately studied yet.
Given a truly POSIX archive with names having more than 100 characters,
I guess that GNU @{b}tar@{ub} up to 1.11.8 will process it as if it were an old
V7 archive, and be fooled by some fields which are coded differently.
So, the question is to decide if the next generation of GNU @{b}tar@{ub} should
produce POSIX format by default, whenever possible, producing archives
older versions of GNU @{b}tar@{ub} might not be able to read correctly.  I fear
that we will have to suffer such a choice one of these days, if we want
GNU @{b}tar@{ub} to go closer to POSIX.  We can rush it.  Another possibility is
to produce the current GNU @{b}tar@{ub} format by default for a few years, but
have GNU @{b}tar@{ub} versions from some 1.POSIX and up able to recognize all
three formats, and let older GNU @{b}tar@{ub} fade out slowly.  Then, we could
switch to producing POSIX format by default, with not much harm to
those still having (very old at that time) GNU @{b}tar@{ub} versions prior to
1.POSIX.

   POSIX format cannot represent very long names, volume headers,
splitting of files in multi-volumes, sparse files, and incremental
dumps; these would be all disallowed if @{b}--posix@{ub} or @{b}POSIXLY_CORRECT@{ub}.
Otherwise, if @{b}tar@{ub} is given long names, or @{b}-[VMSgG]@{ub}, then it should
automatically go non-POSIX.  I think this is easily granted without
much discussion.

   Another point is that only @{b}mtime@{ub} is stored in POSIX archives, while
GNU @{b}tar@{ub} currently also store @{b}atime@{ub} and @{b}ctime@{ub}.  If we want GNU @{b}tar@{ub} to go
closer to POSIX, my choice would be to drop @{b}atime@{ub} and @{b}ctime@{ub} support on
average.  On the other hand, I perceive that full dumps or incremental
dumps need @{b}atime@{ub} and @{b}ctime@{ub} support, so for those special applications,
POSIX has to be avoided altogether.

   A few users requested that @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) be always active by
default, I think that before replying to them, we have to decide if we
want GNU @{b}tar@{ub} to go closer to POSIX on average, while producing files.
My choice would be to go closer to POSIX in the long run.  Besides
possible double reading, I do not see any point of not trying to save
files as sparse when creating archives which are neither POSIX nor
old-V7, so the actual @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) would become selected by default
when producing such archives, whatever the reason is.  So, @{b}--sparse@{ub}
(@{b}-S@{ub}) alone might be redefined to force GNU-format archives, and recover
its previous meaning from this fact.

   GNU-format as it exists now can easily fool other POSIX @{b}tar@{ub}, as it
uses fields which POSIX considers to be part of the file name prefix.
I wonder if it would not be a good idea, in the long run, to try
changing GNU-format so any added field (like @{b}ctime@{ub}, @{b}atime@{ub}, file offset
in subsequent volumes, or sparse file descriptions) be wholly and
always pushed into an extension block, instead of using space in the
POSIX header block.  I could manage to do that portably between future
GNU @{b}tar@{ub}s.  So other POSIX @{b}tar@{ub}s might be at least able to provide kind
of correct listings for the archives produced by GNU @{b}tar@{ub}, if not able
to process them otherwise.

   Using these projected extensions might induce older @{b}tar@{ub}s to fail.
We would use the same approach as for POSIX.  I'll put out a @{b}tar@{ub}
capable of reading POSIXier, yet extended archives, but will not produce
this format by default, in GNU mode.  In a few years, when newer GNU
@{b}tar@{ub}s will have flooded out @{b}tar@{ub} 1.11.X and previous, we could switch to
producing POSIXier extended archives, with no real harm to users, as
almost all existing GNU @{b}tar@{ub}s will be ready to read POSIXier format.  In
fact, I'll do both changes at the same time, in a few years, and just
prepare @{b}tar@{ub} for both changes, without effecting them, from 1.POSIX.
(Both changes: 1--using POSIX convention for getting over 100
characters; 2--avoiding mangling POSIX headers for GNU extensions,
using only POSIX mandated extension techniques).

   So, a future @{b}tar@{ub} will have a @{b}--posix@{ub} flag forcing the usage of truly
POSIX headers, and so, producing archives previous GNU @{b}tar@{ub} will not be
able to read.  So, @{i}once@{ui} pretest will announce that feature, it would be
particularly useful that users test how exchangeable will be archives
between GNU @{b}tar@{ub} with @{b}--posix@{ub} and other POSIX @{b}tar@{ub}.

   In a few years, when GNU @{b}tar@{ub} will produce POSIX headers by default,
@{b}--posix@{ub} will have a strong meaning and will disallow GNU extensions.
But in the meantime, for a long while, @{b}--posix@{ub} in GNU tar will not
disallow GNU extensions like @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}),
@{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}), @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}), or very long file or link names.
However, @{b}--posix@{ub} with GNU extensions will use POSIX headers with
reserved-for-users extensions to headers, and I will be curious to know
how well or bad POSIX @{b}tar@{ub}s will react to these.

   GNU @{b}tar@{ub} prior to 1.POSIX, and after 1.POSIX without @{b}--posix@{ub},
generates and checks @{b}ustar  @{ub}, with two suffixed spaces.  This is
sufficient for older GNU @{b}tar@{ub} not to recognize POSIX archives, and
consequently, wrongly decide those archives are in old V7 format.  It
is a useful bug for me, because GNU @{b}tar@{ub} has other POSIX
incompatibilities, and I need to segregate GNU @{b}tar@{ub} semi-POSIX archives
from truly POSIX archives, for GNU @{b}tar@{ub} should be somewhat compatible
with itself, while migrating closer to latest POSIX standards.  So,
I'll be very careful about how and when I will do the correction.


@endnode

@node "Checksumming" "tar.guide/Checksumming"
@prev "posix"
@toc "Portability"

Checksumming Problems
---------------------

   SunOS and HP-UX @{b}tar@{ub} fail to accept archives created using GNU @{b}tar@{ub}
and containing non-ASCII file names, that is, file names having
characters with the eight bit set, because they use signed checksums,
while GNU @{b}tar@{ub} uses unsigned checksums while creating archives, as per
POSIX standards.  On reading, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} computes both checksums and
accept any.  It is somewhat worrying that a lot of people may go around
doing backup of their files using faulty (or at least non-standard)
software, not learning about it until it's time to restore their
missing files with an incompatible file extractor, or vice versa.

   GNU @{b}tar@{ub} compute checksums both ways, and accept any on read, so GNU
tar can read Sun tapes even with their wrong checksums.  GNU @{b}tar@{ub}
produces the standard checksum, however, raising incompatibilities with
Sun.  That is to say, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} has not been modified to @{i}produce@{ui}
incorrect archives to be read by buggy @{b}tar@{ub}'s.  I've been told that more
recent Sun @{b}tar@{ub} now read standard archives, so maybe Sun did a similar
patch, after all?

   The story seems to be that when Sun first imported @{b}tar@{ub} sources on
their system, they recompiled it without realizing that the checksums
were computed differently, because of a change in the default signing
of @{b}char@{ub}'s in their compiler.  So they started computing checksums
wrongly.  When they later realized their mistake, they merely decided
to stay compatible with it, and with themselves afterwards.
Presumably, but I do not really know, HP-UX has chosen that their @{b}tar@{ub}
archives to be compatible with Sun's.  The current standards do not
favor Sun @{b}tar@{ub} format.  In any case, it now falls on the shoulders of
SunOS and HP-UX users to get a @{b}tar@{ub} able to read the good archives they
receive.


@endnode

