@node "gzip" "tar.guide/gzip"
@next "sparse"
@prev "Compression"
@toc "Compression"

Creating and Reading Compressed Archives
----------------------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

@{b}-z@{ub}
@{b}--gzip@{ub}
@{b}--ungzip@{ub}
     Filter the archive through @{b}gzip@{ub}.

   Some format parameters must be taken into consideration when
modifying an archive: .  Compressed archives cannot be modified.

   You can use @{b}--gzip@{ub} and @{b}--gunzip@{ub} on physical devices (tape drives,
etc.) and remote files as well as on normal files; data to or from such
devices or remote files is reblocked by another copy of the @{b}tar@{ub} program
to enforce the specified (or default) record size.  The default
compression parameters are used; if you need to override them, avoid
the @{b}--gzip@{ub} (@{b}--gunzip@{ub}, @{b}--ungzip@{ub}, @{b}-z@{ub}) option and run @{b}gzip@{ub} explicitly.
(Or set the @{b}GZIP@{ub} environment variable.)

   The @{b}--gzip@{ub} (@{b}--gunzip@{ub}, @{b}--ungzip@{ub}, @{b}-z@{ub}) option does not work with the
@{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) option, or with the @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}), @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}),
@{b}--concatenate@{ub} (@{b}--catenate@{ub}, @{b}-A@{ub}), or @{b}--delete@{ub} operations.

   It is not exact to say that GNU @{b}tar@{ub} is to work in concert with @{b}gzip@{ub}
in a way similar to @{b}zip@{ub}, say.  Surely, it is possible that @{b}tar@{ub} and @{b}gzip@{ub}
be done with a single call, like in:

     $ tar cfz archive.tar.gz subdir

to save all of @{b}subdir@{ub} into a @{b}gzip@{ub}'ed archive.  Later you can do:

     $ tar xfz archive.tar.gz

to explode and unpack.

   The difference is that the whole archive is compressed.  With @{b}zip@{ub},
archive members are archived individually.  @{b}tar@{ub}'s method yields better
compression.  On the other hand, one can view the contents of a @{b}zip@{ub}
archive without having to decompress it.  As for the @{b}tar@{ub} and @{b}gzip@{ub}
tandem, you need to decompress the archive to see its contents.
However, this may be done without needing disk space, by using pipes
internally:

     $ tar tfz archive.tar.gz

   About corrupted compressed archives: @{b}gzip@{ub}'ed files have no
redundancy, for maximum compression.  The adaptive nature of the
compression scheme means that the compression tables are implicitly
spread all over the archive.  If you lose a few blocks, the dynamic
construction of the compression tables becomes unsychronized, and there
is little chance that you could recover later in the archive.

   There are pending suggestions for having a per-volume or per-file
compression in GNU @{b}tar@{ub}.  This would allow for viewing the contents
without decompression, and for resynchronizing decompression at every
volume or file, in case of corrupted archives.  Doing so, we might
loose some compressibility.  But this would have make recovering easier.
So, there are pros and cons.  We'll see!

@{b}-Z@{ub}
@{b}--compress@{ub}
@{b}--uncompress@{ub}
     Filter the archive through @{b}compress@{ub}.  Otherwise like @{b}--gzip@{ub}
     (@{b}--gunzip@{ub}, @{b}--ungzip@{ub}, @{b}-z@{ub}).

@{b}--use-compress-program=PROG@{ub}
     Filter through PROG (must accept @{b}-d@{ub}).

   @{b}--compress@{ub} (@{b}--uncompress@{ub}, @{b}-Z@{ub}) stores an archive in compressed
format.  This option is useful in saving time over networks and space
in pipes, and when storage space is at a premium.  @{b}--compress@{ub}
(@{b}--uncompress@{ub}, @{b}-Z@{ub}) causes @{b}tar@{ub} to compress when writing the archive, or
to uncompress when reading the archive.

   To perform compression and uncompression on the archive, @{b}tar@{ub} runs
the @{b}compress@{ub} utility.  @{b}tar@{ub} uses the default compression parameters; if
you need to override them, avoid the @{b}--compress@{ub} (@{b}--uncompress@{ub}, @{b}-Z@{ub})
option and run the @{b}compress@{ub} utility explicitly.  It is useful to be
able to call the @{b}compress@{ub} utility from within @{b}tar@{ub} because the @{b}compress@{ub}
utility by itself cannot access remote tape drives.

   The @{b}--compress@{ub} (@{b}--uncompress@{ub}, @{b}-Z@{ub}) option will not work in
conjunction with the @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) option or the @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}),
@{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}), @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}) and @{b}--delete@{ub} operations.  See @{"Operations" link "Operations"},
for more information on these operations.

   If there is no compress utility available, @{b}tar@{ub} will report an error.
@{b}Please note@{ub} that the @{b}compress@{ub} program may be covered by a patent, and
therefore we recommend you stop using it.

@{b}--compress@{ub}
@{b}--uncompress@{ub}
@{b}-z@{ub}
@{b}-Z@{ub}
     When this option is specified, @{b}tar@{ub} will compress (when writing an
     archive), or uncompress (when reading an archive).  Used in
     conjunction with the @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}), @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}), @{b}--list@{ub}
     (@{b}-t@{ub}) and @{b}--compare@{ub} (@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}) operations.

   You can have archives be compressed by using the @{b}--gzip@{ub} (@{b}--gunzip@{ub},
@{b}--ungzip@{ub}, @{b}-z@{ub}) option.  This will arrange for @{b}tar@{ub} to use the @{b}gzip@{ub}
program to be used to compress or uncompress the archive wren writing
or reading it.

   To use the older, obsolete, @{b}compress@{ub} program, use the @{b}--compress@{ub}
(@{b}--uncompress@{ub}, @{b}-Z@{ub}) option.  The GNU Project recommends you not use
@{b}compress@{ub}, because there is a patent covering the algorithm it uses.
You could be sued for patent infringment merely by running @{b}compress@{ub}.

   I have one question, or maybe it's a suggestion if there isn't a way
to do it now. I would like to use @{b}--gzip@{ub} (@{b}--gunzip@{ub}, @{b}--ungzip@{ub}, @{b}-z@{ub}), but
I'd also like the output to be fed through a program like GNU @{b}ecc@{ub}
(actually, right now that's @{b}exactly@{ub} what I'd like to use :-)),
basically adding ECC protection on top of compression.  It seems as if
this should be quite easy to do, but I can't work out exactly how to go
about it.  Of course, I can pipe the standard output of @{b}tar@{ub} through
@{b}ecc@{ub}, but then I lose (though I haven't started using it yet, I confess)
the ability to have @{b}tar@{ub} use @{b}rmt@{ub} for it's I/O (I think).

   I think the most straightforward thing would be to let me specify a
general set of filters outboard of compression (preferably ordered, so
the order can be automatically reversed on input operations, and with
the options they require specifiable), but beggars shouldn't be
choosers and anything you decide on would be fine with me.

   By the way, I like @{b}ecc@{ub} but if (as the comments say) it can't deal
with loss of block sync, I'm tempted to throw some time at adding that
capability.  Supposing I were to actually do such a thing and get it
(apparantly) working, do you accept contributed changes to utilities
like that?  (Leigh Clayton @{b}loc@soliton.com@{ub}, May 1995).

   Isn't that exactly the role of the @{b}--use-compress-prog=PROGRAM@{ub}
option?  I never tried it myself, but I suspect you may want to write a
PROG script or program able to filter stdin to stdout to way you want.
It should recognize the @{b}-d@{ub} option, for when extraction is needed rather
than creation.

   It has been reported that if one writes compressed data (through the
@{b}--gzip@{ub} (@{b}--gunzip@{ub}, @{b}--ungzip@{ub}, @{b}-z@{ub}) or @{b}--compress@{ub} (@{b}--uncompress@{ub}, @{b}-Z@{ub})
options) to a DLT and tries to use the DLT compression mode, the data
will actually get bigger and one will end up with less space on the
tape.


@endnode

@node "sparse" "tar.guide/sparse"
@prev "gzip"
@toc "Compression"

Archiving Sparse Files
----------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

@{b}-S@{ub}
@{b}--sparse@{ub}
     Handle sparse files efficiently.

   This option causes all files to be put in the archive to be tested
for sparseness, and handled specially if they are.  The @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub})
option is useful when many @{b}dbm@{ub} files, for example, are being backed up.
Using this option dramatically decreases the amount of space needed to
store such a file.

   In later versions, this option may be removed, and the testing and
treatment of sparse files may be done automatically with any special
GNU options.  For now, it is an option needing to be specified on the
command line with the creation or updating of an archive.

   Files in the filesystem occasionally have "holes."  A hole in a file
is a section of the file's contents which was never written.  The
contents of a hole read as all zeros.  On many operating systems,
actual disk storage is not allocated for holes, but they are counted in
the length of the file.  If you archive such a file, @{b}tar@{ub} could create
an archive longer than the original.  To have @{b}tar@{ub} attempt to recognize
the holes in a file, use @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}).  When you use the @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub})
option, then, for any file using less disk space than would be expected
from its length, @{b}tar@{ub} searches the file for consecutive stretches of
zeros.  It then records in the archive for the file where the
consecutive stretches of zeros are, and only archives the "real
contents" of the file.  On extraction (using @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) is not
needed on extraction) any such files have hols created wherever the
continuous stretches of zeros were found.  Thus, if you use @{b}--sparse@{ub}
(@{b}-S@{ub}), @{b}tar@{ub} archives won't take more space than the original.

   A file is sparse if it contains blocks of zeros whose existence is
recorded, but that have no space allocated on disk.  When you specify
the @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) option in conjunction with the @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub})
operation, @{b}tar@{ub} tests all files for sparseness while archiving.  If @{b}tar@{ub}
finds a file to be sparse, it uses a sparse representation of the file
in the archive.  See @{"create" link "create"}, for more information about creating
archives.

   @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) is useful when archiving files, such as dbm files,
likely to contain many nulls.  This option dramatically decreases the
amount of space needed to store such an archive.

@{b}     Please Note:@{ub} Always use @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) when performing file system
     backups, to avoid archiving the expanded forms of files stored
     sparsely in the system.

     Even if your system has no sparse files currently, some may be
     created in the future.  If you use @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) while making file
     system backups as a matter of course, you can be assured the
     archive will never take more space on the media than the files
     take on disk (otherwise, archiving a disk filled with sparse files
     might take hundreds of tapes).

@{b}   tar@{ub} ignores the @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) option when reading an archive.

@{b}--sparse@{ub}
@{b}-S@{ub}
     Files stored sparsely in the file system are represented sparsely
     in the archive.  Use in conjunction with write operations.

   However, users should be well aware that at archive creation time,
GNU @{b}tar@{ub} still has to read whole disk file to locate the @{i}holes@{ui}, and so,
even if sparse files use little space on disk and in the archive, they
may sometimes require inordinate amount of time for reading and
examining all-zero blocks of a file.  Although it works, it's painfully
slow for a large (sparse) file, even though the resulting tar archive
may be small.  (One user reports that dumping a @{b}core@{ub} file of over 400
megabytes, but with only about 3 megabytes of actual data, took about 9
minutes on a Sun Sparstation ELC, with full CPU utilisation.)

   This reading is required in all cases and is not related to the fact
the @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub}) option is used or not, so by merely @{i}not@{ui} using the
option, you are not saving time(1).

   Programs like @{b}dump@{ub} do not have to read the entire file; by examining
the file system directly, they can determine in advance exactly where
the holes are and thus avoid reading through them.  The only data it
need read are the actual allocated data blocks.  GNU @{b}tar@{ub} uses a more
portable and straightforward archiving approach, it would be fairly
difficult that it does otherwise.  Elizabeth Zwicky writes to
@{b}comp.unix.internals@{ub}, on 1990-12-10:

     What I did say is that you cannot tell the difference between a
     hole and an equivalent number of nulls without reading raw blocks.
     @{b}st_blocks@{ub} at best tells you how many holes there are; it doesn't
     tell you @{i}where@{ui}.  Just as programs may, conceivably, care what
     @{b}st_blocks@{ub} is (care to name one that does?), they may also care
     where the holes are (I have no examples of this one either, but
     it's equally imaginable).

     I conclude from this that good archivers are not portable.  One can
     arguably conclude that if you want a portable program, you can in
     good conscience restore files with as many holes as possible,
     since you can't get it right.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) Well!  We should say the whole truth, here.  When @{b}--sparse@{ub} (@{b}-S@{ub})
is selected while creating an archive, the current @{b}tar@{ub} algorithm
requires sparse files to be read twice, not once.  We hope to develop a
new archive format for saving sparse files in which one pass will be
sufficient.


@endnode

