GNU Extensions to the Archive Format
====================================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   The GNU format uses additional file types to describe new types of
files in an archive.  These are listed below.

@{b}GNUTYPE_DUMPDIR@{ub}
@{b}'D'@{ub}
     This represents a directory and a list of files created by the
     @{b}--incremental@{ub} (@{b}-G@{ub}) option.  The @{b}size@{ub} field gives the total size of
     the associated list of files.  Each file name is preceded by
     either a @{b}Y@{ub} (the file should be in this archive) or an @{b}N@{ub}.  (The
     file is a directory, or is not stored in the archive.)  Each file
     name is terminated by a null.  There is an additional null after
     the last file name.

@{b}GNUTYPE_MULTIVOL@{ub}
@{b}'M'@{ub}
     This represents a file continued from another volume of a
     multi-volume archive created with the @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) option.
     The original type of the file is not given here.  The @{b}size@{ub} field
     gives the maximum size of this piece of the file (assuming the
     volume does not end before the file is written out).  The @{b}offset@{ub}
     field gives the offset from the beginning of the file where this
     part of the file begins.  Thus @{b}size@{ub} plus @{b}offset@{ub} should equal the
     original size of the file.

@{b}GNUTYPE_SPARSE@{ub}
@{b}'S'@{ub}
     This flag indicates that we are dealing with a sparse file.  Note
     that archiving a sparse file requires special operations to find
     holes in the file, which mark the positions of these holes, along
     with the number of bytes of data to be found after the hole.

@{b}GNUTYPE_VOLHDR@{ub}
@{b}'V'@{ub}
     This file type is used to mark the volume header that was given
     with the @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) option when the
     archive was created.  The @{b}name@{ub} field contains the @{b}name@{ub} given after
     the @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) option.  The @{b}size@{ub}
     field is zero.  Only the first file in each volume of an archive
     should have this type.

   You may have trouble reading a GNU format archive on a non-GNU
system if the options @{b}--incremental@{ub} (@{b}-G@{ub}), @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}), @{b}--sparse@{ub}
(@{b}-S@{ub}), or @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) were used when
writing the archive.  In general, if @{b}tar@{ub} does not use the GNU-added
fields of the header, other versions of @{b}tar@{ub} should be able to read the
archive.  Otherwise, the @{b}tar@{ub} program will give an error, the most
likely one being a checksum error.


@endnode

@node "cpio" "tar.guide/cpio"
@prev "Extensions"
@toc "Formats"

Comparison of @{b}tar@{ub} and @{b}cpio@{ub}
==========================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   The @{b}cpio@{ub} archive formats, like @{b}tar@{ub}, do have maximum pathname
lengths.  The binary and old ASCII formats have a max path length of
256, and the new ASCII and CRC ASCII formats have a max path length of
1024.  GNU @{b}cpio@{ub} can read and write archives with arbitrary pathname
lengths, but other @{b}cpio@{ub} implementations may crash unexplainedly trying
to read them.

@{b}   tar@{ub} handles symbolic links in the form in which it comes in BSD;
@{b}cpio@{ub} doesn't handle symbolic links in the form in which it comes in
System V prior to SVR4, and some vendors may have added symlinks to
their system without enhancing @{b}cpio@{ub} to know about them.  Others may
have enhanced it in a way other than the way I did it at Sun, and which
was adopted by AT&T (and which is, I think, also present in the @{b}cpio@{ub}
that Berkeley picked up from AT&T and put into a later BSD release--I
think I gave them my changes).

   (SVR4 does some funny stuff with @{b}tar@{ub}; basically, its @{b}cpio@{ub} can handle
@{b}tar@{ub} format input, and write it on output, and it probably handles
symbolic links.  They may not have bothered doing anything to enhance
@{b}tar@{ub} as a result.)

@{b}   cpio@{ub} handles special files; traditional @{b}tar@{ub} doesn't.

@{b}   tar@{ub} comes with V7, System III, System V, and BSD source; @{b}cpio@{ub} comes
only with System III, System V, and later BSD (4.3-tahoe and later).

@{b}   tar@{ub}'s way of handling multiple hard links to a file can handle file
systems that support 32-bit inumbers (e.g., the BSD file system); @{b}cpio@{ub}s
way requires you to play some games (in its "binary" format, i-numbers
are only 16 bits, and in its "portable ASCII" format, they're 18
bits--it would have to play games with the "file system ID" field of
the header to make sure that the file system ID/i-number pairs of
different files were always different), and I don't know which @{b}cpio@{ub}s,
if any, play those games.  Those that don't might get confused and
think two files are the same file when they're not, and make hard links
between them.

@{b}   tar@{ub}s way of handling multiple hard links to a file places only one
copy of the link on the tape, but the name attached to that copy is the
@{i}only@{ui} one you can use to retrieve the file; @{b}cpio@{ub}s way puts one copy for
every link, but you can retrieve it using any of the names.

     What type of check sum (if any) is used, and how is this
     calculated.

   See the attached manual pages for @{b}tar@{ub} and @{b}cpio@{ub} format.  @{b}tar@{ub} uses a
checksum which is the sum of all the bytes in the @{b}tar@{ub} header for a
file; @{b}cpio@{ub} uses no checksum.

     If anyone knows why @{b}cpio@{ub} was made when @{b}tar@{ub} was present at the unix
     scene,

   It wasn't.  @{b}cpio@{ub} first showed up in PWB/UNIX 1.0; no
generally-available version of UNIX had @{b}tar@{ub} at the time.  I don't know
whether any version that was generally available @{i}within AT&T@{ui} had @{b}tar@{ub},
or, if so, whether the people within AT&T who did @{b}cpio@{ub} knew about it.

   On restore, if there is a corruption on a tape @{b}tar@{ub} will stop at that
point, while @{b}cpio@{ub} will skip over it and try to restore the rest of the
files.

   The main difference is just in the command syntax and header format.

@{b}   tar@{ub} is a little more tape-oriented in that everything is blocked to
start on a record boundary.

     Is there any differences between the ability to recover crashed
     archives between the two of them. (Is there any chance of
     recovering crashed archives at all.)

   Theoretically it should be easier under @{b}tar@{ub} since the blocking lets
you find a header with some variation of @{b}dd skip=NN@{ub}.  However, modern
@{b}cpio@{ub}'s and variations have an option to just search for the next file
header after an error with a reasonable chance of re-syncing.  However,
lots of tape driver software won't allow you to continue past a media
error which should be the only reason for getting out of sync unless a
file changed sizes while you were writing the archive.

     If anyone knows why @{b}cpio@{ub} was made when @{b}tar@{ub} was present at the unix
     scene, please tell me about this too.

   Probably because it is more media efficient (by not blocking
everything and using only the space needed for the headers where @{b}tar@{ub}
always uses 512 bytes per file header) and it knows how to archive
special files.

   You might want to look at the freely available alternatives.  The
major ones are @{b}afio@{ub}, GNU @{b}tar@{ub}, and @{b}pax@{ub}, each of which have their own
extensions with some backwards compatibility.

   Sparse files were @{b}tar@{ub}red as sparse files (which you can easily test,
because the resulting archive gets smaller, and GNU @{b}cpio@{ub} can no longer
read it).


@endnode

