Device Selection and Switching
==============================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

@{b}-f [HOSTNAME:]FILE@{ub}
@{b}--file=[HOSTNAME:]FILE@{ub}
     Use archive file or device FILE on HOSTNAME.

   This option is used to specify the file name of the archive @{b}tar@{ub}
works on.

   If the file name is @{b}-@{ub}, @{b}tar@{ub} reads the archive from standard input
(when listing or extracting), or writes it to standard output (when
creating).  If the @{b}-@{ub} file name is given when updating an archive, @{b}tar@{ub}
will read the original archive from its standard input, and will write
the entire new archive to its standard output.

   If the file name contains a @{b}:@{ub}, it is interpreted as @{b}hostname:file
name@{ub}.  If the HOSTNAME contains an @{i}at@{ui} sign (@{b}@@{ub}), it is treated as
@{b}user@hostname:file name@{ub}.  In either case, @{b}tar@{ub} will invoke the command
@{b}rsh@{ub} (or @{b}remsh@{ub}) to start up an @{b}/etc/rmt@{ub} on the remote machine.  If you
give an alternate login name, it will be given to the @{b}rsh@{ub}.  Naturally,
the remote machine must have an executable @{b}/etc/rmt@{ub}.  This program is
free software from the University of California, and a copy of the
source code can be found with the sources for @{b}tar@{ub}; it's compiled and
installed by default.

   If this option is not given, but the environment variable @{b}TAPE@{ub} is
set, its value is used; otherwise, old versions of @{b}tar@{ub} used a default
archive name (which was picked when @{b}tar@{ub} was compiled).  The default is
normally set up to be the @{i}first@{ui} tape drive or other transportable I/O
medium on the system.

   Starting with version 1.11.5, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} uses standard input and
standard output as the default device, and I will not try anymore
supporting automatic device detection at installation time.  This was
failing really in too many cases, it was hopeless.  This is now
completely left to the installer to override standard input and standard
output for default device, if this seems preferrable to him/her.
Further, I think @{i}most@{ui} actual usages of @{b}tar@{ub} are done with pipes or
disks, not really tapes, cartridges or diskettes.

   Some users think that using standard input and output is running
after trouble.  This could lead to a nasty surprise on your screen if
you forget to specify an output file name--especially if you are going
through a network or terminal server capable of buffering large amounts
of output.  We had so many bug reports in that area of configuring
default tapes automatically, and so many contradicting requests, that
we finally consider the problem to be portably intractable.  We could
of course use something like @{b}/dev/tape@{ub} as a default, but this is @{i}also@{ui}
running after various kind of trouble, going from hung processes to
accidental destruction of real tapes.  After having seen all this mess,
using standard input and output as a default really sounds like the
only clean choice left, and a very useful one too.

   GNU @{b}tar@{ub} reads and writes archive in records, I suspect this is the
main reason why block devices are preferred over character devices.
Most probably, block devices are more efficient too.  The installer
could also check for @{b}DEFTAPE@{ub} in @{b}<sys/mtio.h>@{ub}.

@{b}--force-local@{ub}
     Archive file is local even if it contains a colon.

@{b}--rsh-command=COMMAND@{ub}
     Use remote COMMAND instead of @{b}rsh@{ub}.  This option exists so that
     people who use something other than the standard @{b}rsh@{ub} (e.g., a
     Kerberized @{b}rsh@{ub}) can access a remote device.

     When this command is not used, the shell command found when the
     @{b}tar@{ub} program was installed is used instead.  This is the first
     found of @{b}/usr/ucb/rsh@{ub}, @{b}/usr/bin/remsh@{ub}, @{b}/usr/bin/rsh@{ub}, @{b}/usr/bsd/rsh@{ub}
     or @{b}/usr/bin/nsh@{ub}.  The installer may have overriden this by
     defining the environment variable @{b}RSH@{ub} @{i}at installation time@{ui}.

@{b}-[0-7][lmh]@{ub}
     Specify drive and density.

@{b}-M@{ub}
@{b}--multi-volume@{ub}
     Create/list/extract multi-volume archive.

     This option causes @{b}tar@{ub} to write a @{i}multi-volume@{ui} archive--one that
     may be larger than will fit on the medium used to hold it.  See
     @{"Multi-Volume Archives" link "Multi-Volume Archives"}.

@{b}-L NUM@{ub}
@{b}--tape-length=NUM@{ub}
     Change tape after writing NUM x 1024 bytes.

     This option might be useful when your tape drivers do not properly
     detect end of physical tapes.  By being slightly conservative on
     the maximum tape length, you might avoid the problem entirely.

@{b}-F FILE@{ub}
@{b}--info-script=FILE@{ub}
@{b}--new-volume-script=FILE@{ub}
     Execute @{b}file@{ub} at end of each tape.  This implies @{b}--multi-volume@{ub}
     (@{b}-M@{ub}).


@endnode

@node "Remote Tape Server" "tar.guide/Remote Tape Server"
@next "Common Problems and Solutions"
@prev "Device"
@toc "Media"

The Remote Tape Server
======================

   In order to access the tape drive on a remote machine, @{b}tar@{ub} uses the
remote tape server written at the University of California at Berkeley.
The remote tape server must be installed as @{b}/etc/rmt@{ub} on any machine
whose tape drive you want to use.  @{b}tar@{ub} calls @{b}/etc/rmt@{ub} by running an @{b}rsh@{ub}
or @{b}remsh@{ub} to the remote machine, optionally using a different login name
if one is supplied.

   A copy of the source for the remote tape server is provided.  It is
Copyright (C) 1983 by the Regents of the University of California, but
can be freely distributed.  Instructions for compiling and installing
it are included in the @{b}Makefile@{ub}.

   Unless you use the @{b}--absolute-names@{ub} (@{b}-P@{ub}) option, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} will not
allow you to create an archive that contains absolute file names (a
file name beginning with @{b}/@{ub}.) If you try, @{b}tar@{ub} will automatically remove
the leading @{b}/@{ub} from the file names it stores in the archive.  It will
also type a warning message telling you what it is doing.

   When reading an archive that was created with a different @{b}tar@{ub}
program, GNU @{b}tar@{ub} automatically extracts entries in the archive which
have absolute file names as if the file names were not absolute.  This
is an important feature.  A visitor here once gave a @{b}tar@{ub} tape to an
operator to restore; the operator used Sun @{b}tar@{ub} instead of GNU @{b}tar@{ub}, and
the result was that it replaced large portions of our @{b}/bin@{ub} and friends
with versions from the tape; needless to say, we were unhappy about
having to recover the file system from backup tapes.

   For example, if the archive contained a file @{b}/usr/bin/computoy@{ub}, GNU
@{b}tar@{ub} would extract the file to @{b}usr/bin/computoy@{ub}, relative to the current
directory.  If you want to extract the files in an archive to the same
absolute names that they had when the archive was created, you should
do a @{b}cd /@{ub} before extracting the files from the archive, or you should
either use the @{b}--absolute-names@{ub} (@{b}-P@{ub}) option, or use the command @{b}tar -C
/ ...@{ub}.

   Some versions of Unix (Ultrix 3.1 is know to have this problem), can
claim that a short write near the end of a tape succeeded, when it
actually failed.  This will result in the -M option not working
correctly.  The best workaround at the moment is to use a significantly
larger blocking factor than the default 20.

   In order to update an archive, @{b}tar@{ub} must be able to backspace the
archive in order to reread or rewrite a record that was just read (or
written).  This is currently possible only on two kinds of files: normal
disk files (or any other file that can be backspaced with @{b}lseek@{ub}), and
industry-standard 9-track magnetic tape (or any other kind of tape that
can be backspaced with the @{b}MTIOCTOP@{ub} @{b}ioctl@{ub}.

   This means that the @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}), @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}), @{b}--concatenate@{ub}
(@{b}--catenate@{ub}, @{b}-A@{ub}), and @{b}--delete@{ub} commands will not work on any other kind
of file.  Some media simply cannot be backspaced, which means these
commands and options will never be able to work on them.  These
non-backspacing media include pipes and cartridge tape drives.

   Some other media can be backspaced, and @{b}tar@{ub} will work on them once
@{b}tar@{ub} is modified to do so.

   Archives created with the @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}), @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}
(@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}), and @{b}--incremental@{ub} (@{b}-G@{ub}) options may not be readable
by other version of @{b}tar@{ub}.  In particular, restoring a file that was
split over a volume boundary will require some careful work with @{b}dd@{ub}, if
it can be done at all.  Other versions of @{b}tar@{ub} may also create an empty
file whose name is that of the volume header.  Some versions of @{b}tar@{ub} may
create normal files instead of directories archived with the
@{b}--incremental@{ub} (@{b}-G@{ub}) option.


@endnode

