@endnode

@node "Tape Positioning" "tar.guide/Tape Positioning"
@next "mt"
@prev "Many"
@toc "Many"

Tape Positions and Tape Marks
-----------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   Just as archives can store more than one file from the file system,
tapes can store more than one archive file.  To keep track of where
archive files (or any other type of file stored on tape) begin and end,
tape archive devices write magnetic @{i}tape marks@{ui} on the archive media.
Tape drives write one tape mark between files, two at the end of all
the file entries.

   If you think of data as a series of records "rrrr"'s, and tape marks
as "*"'s, a tape might look like the following:

     rrrr*rrrrrr*rrrrr*rr*rrrrr**-------------------------

   Tape devices read and write tapes using a read/write @{i}tape head@{ui}--a
physical part of the device which can only access one point on the tape
at a time.  When you use @{b}tar@{ub} to read or write archive data from a tape
device, the device will begin reading or writing from wherever on the
tape the tape head happens to be, regardless of which archive or what
part of the archive the tape head is on.  Before writing an archive,
you should make sure that no data on the tape will be overwritten
(unless it is no longer needed).  Before reading an archive, you should
make sure the tape head is at the beginning of the archive you want to
read.  (The @{b}restore@{ub} script will find the archive automatically.  .  ).
See @{"mt" link "mt"}, for an explanation of the tape moving utility.

   If you want to add new archive file entries to a tape, you should
advance the tape to the end of the existing file entries, backspace
over the last tape mark, and write the new archive file.  If you were
to add two archives to the example above, the tape might look like the
following:

     rrrr*rrrrrr*rrrrr*rr*rrrrr*rrr*rrrr**----------------


@endnode

@node "mt" "tar.guide/mt"
@prev "Tape Positioning"
@toc "Many"

The @{b}mt@{ub} Utility
--------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   See @{"Blocking Factor" link "Blocking Factor"}.

   You can use the @{b}mt@{ub} utility to advance or rewind a tape past a
specified number of archive files on the tape.  This will allow you to
move to the beginning of an archive before extracting or reading it, or
to the end of all the archives before writing a new one.

   The syntax of the @{b}mt@{ub} command is:

     mt [-f TAPENAME] OPERATION [NUMBER]

   where TAPENAME is the name of the tape device, NUMBER is the number
of times an operation is performed (with a default of one), and
OPERATION is one of the following:

@{b}eof@{ub}
@{b}weof@{ub}
     Writes NUMBER tape marks at the current position on the tape.

@{b}fsf@{ub}
     Moves tape position forward NUMBER files.

@{b}bsf@{ub}
     Moves tape position back NUMBER files.

@{b}rewind@{ub}
     Rewinds the tape. (Ignores NUMBER).

@{b}offline@{ub}
@{b}rewoff1@{ub}
     Rewinds the tape and takes the tape device off-line. (Ignores
     NUMBER).

@{b}status@{ub}
     Prints status information about the tape unit.

   If you don't specify a TAPENAME, @{b}mt@{ub} uses the environment variable
TAPE; if TAPE does not exist, @{b}mt@{ub} uses the device @{b}/dev/rmt12@{ub}.

@{b}   mt@{ub} returns a 0 exit status when the operation(s) were successful, 1
if the command was unrecognized, and 2 if an operation failed.

   If you use @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}) with the @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V
ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) option specified, @{b}tar@{ub} will read an archive label (the
tape head has to be positioned on it) and print an error if the archive
label doesn't match the ARCHIVE-NAME specified.  ARCHIVE-NAME can be
any regular expression.  If the labels match, @{b}tar@{ub} extracts the archive.
See @{"label" link "label"}.  .   @{b}tar --list --label@{ub} will cause @{b}tar@{ub} to print the label.


@endnode

@node "Using Multiple Tapes" "tar.guide/Using Multiple Tapes"
@next "label"
@prev "Many"
@toc "Media"

Using Multiple Tapes
====================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   Often you might want to write a large archive, one larger than will
fit on the actual tape you are using.  In such a case, you can run
multiple @{b}tar@{ub} commands, but this can be inconvenient, particularly if you
are using options like @{b}--exclude=PATTERN@{ub} or dumping entire filesystems.
Therefore, @{b}tar@{ub} supports multiple tapes automatically.

   Use @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) on the command line, and then @{b}tar@{ub} will, when
it reaches the end of the tape, prompt for another tape, and continue
the archive.  Each tape will have an independent archive, and can be
read without needing the other.  (As an exception to this, the file
that @{b}tar@{ub} was archiving when it ran out of tape will usually be split
between the two archives; in this case you need to extract from the
first archive, using @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}), and then put in the second
tape when prompted, so @{b}tar@{ub} can restore both halves of the file.)

   GNU @{b}tar@{ub} multi-volume archives do not use a truly portable format.
You need GNU @{b}tar@{ub} at both end to process them properly.

   When prompting for a new tape, @{b}tar@{ub} accepts any of the following
responses:

@{b}?@{ub}
     Request @{b}tar@{ub} to explain possible responses

@{b}q@{ub}
     Request @{b}tar@{ub} to exit immediately.

@{b}n FILE NAME@{ub}
     Request @{b}tar@{ub} to write the next volume on the file FILE NAME.

@{b}!@{ub}
     Request @{b}tar@{ub} to run a subshell.

@{b}y@{ub}
     Request @{b}tar@{ub} to begin writing the next volume.

   (You should only type @{b}y@{ub} after you have changed the tape; otherwise
@{b}tar@{ub} will write over the volume it just finished.)

   If you want more elaborate behavior than this, give @{b}tar@{ub} the
@{b}--info-script=SCRIPT-NAME@{ub} (@{b}--new-volume-script=SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}, @{b}-F
SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}) option.  The file SCRIPT-NAME is expected to be a program
(or shell script) to be run instead of the normal prompting procedure.
When the program finishes, @{b}tar@{ub} will immediately begin writing the next
volume.  The behavior of the @{b}n@{ub} response to the normal tape-change
prompt is not available if you use @{b}--info-script=SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}
(@{b}--new-volume-script=SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}, @{b}-F SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}).

   The method @{b}tar@{ub} uses to detect end of tape is not perfect, and fails
on some operating systems or on some devices.  You can use the
@{b}--tape-length=1024-SIZE@{ub} (@{b}-L 1024-SIZE@{ub}) option if @{b}tar@{ub} can't detect the
end of the tape itself.  This option selects @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub})
automatically.  The SIZE argument should then be the usable size of the
tape.  But for many devices, and floppy disks in particular, this
option is never required for real, as far as we know.

   The volume number used by @{b}tar@{ub} in its tape-change prompt can be
changed; if you give the @{b}--volno-file=FILE-OF-NUMBER@{ub} option, then
FILE-OF-NUMBER should be an unexisting file to be created, or else, a
file already containing a decimal number.  That number will be used as
the volume number of the first volume written.  When @{b}tar@{ub} is finished,
it will rewrite the file with the now-current volume number.  (This
does not change the volume number written on a tape label, as per
@{"label" link "label"}, it @{i}only@{ui} affects the number used in the prompt.)

   If you want @{b}tar@{ub} to cycle through a series of tape drives, then you
can use the @{b}n@{ub} response to the tape-change prompt.  This is error prone,
however, and doesn't work at all with @{b}--info-script=SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}
(@{b}--new-volume-script=SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}, @{b}-F SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}).  Therefore, if you
give @{b}tar@{ub} multiple @{b}--file=ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub} (@{b}-f ARCHIVE-NAME@{ub}) options, then
the specified files will be used, in sequence, as the successive volumes
of the archive.  Only when the first one in the sequence needs to be
used again will @{b}tar@{ub} prompt for a tape change (or run the info script).

   Multi-volume archives

   With @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}), @{b}tar@{ub} will not abort when it cannot read or
write any more data.  Instead, it will ask you to prepare a new volume.
If the archive is on a magnetic tape, you should change tapes now; if
the archive is on a floppy disk, you should change disks, etc.

   Each volume of a multi-volume archive is an independent @{b}tar@{ub} archive,
complete in itself.  For example, you can list or extract any volume
alone; just don't specify @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}).  However, if one file in
the archive is split across volumes, the only way to extract it
successfully is with a multi-volume extract command @{b}--extract
--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-xM@{ub}) starting on or before the volume where the file
begins.

   For example, let's presume someone has two tape drives on a system
named @{b}/dev/tape0@{ub} and @{b}/dev/tape1@{ub}.  For having GNU @{b}tar@{ub} to switch to the
second drive when it needs to write the second tape, and then back to
the first tape, etc., just do either of:

     $ tar --create --multi-volume --file=/dev/tape0 --file=/dev/tape1 FILES
     $ tar cMff /dev/tape0 /dev/tape1 FILES


 @{" Multi-Volume Archives      " link "Multi-Volume Archives"}  Archives Longer than One Tape or Disk
 @{" Tape Files                 " link "Tape Files"}  Tape Files


@endnode

@node "Multi-Volume Archives" "tar.guide/Multi-Volume Archives"
@next "Tape Files"
@prev "Using Multiple Tapes"
@toc "Using Multiple Tapes"

Archives Longer than One Tape or Disk
-------------------------------------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   To create an archive that is larger than will fit on a single unit of
the media, use the @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) option in conjunction with the
@{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) option (see @{"create" link "create"}).  A @{i}multi-volume@{ui} archive can be
manipulated like any other archive (provided the @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub})
option is specified), but is stored on more than one tape or disk.

   When you specify @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}), @{b}tar@{ub} does not report an error
when it comes to the end of an archive volume (when reading), or the
end of the media (when writing).  Instead, it prompts you to load a new
storage volume.  If the archive is on a magnetic tape, you should
change tapes when you see the prompt; if the archive is on a floppy
disk, you should change disks; etc.

   You can read each individual volume of a multi-volume archive as if
it were an archive by itself.  For example, to list the contents of one
volume, use @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}), without @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) specified.  To
extract an archive member from one volume (assuming it is described
that volume), use @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}), again without @{b}--multi-volume@{ub}
(@{b}-M@{ub}).

   If an archive member is split across volumes (ie. its entry begins on
one volume of the media and ends on another), you need to specify
@{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) to extract it successfully.  In this case, you
should load the volume where the archive member starts, and use @{b}tar
--extract --multi-volume@{ub}--@{b}tar@{ub} will prompt for later volumes as it needs
them.  See @{"extracting archives" link "extracting archives"}, for more information about extracting
archives.

   @{b}--info-script=SCRIPT-NAME@{ub} (@{b}--new-volume-script=SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}, @{b}-F
SCRIPT-NAME@{ub}) is like @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}), except that @{b}tar@{ub} does not
prompt you directly to change media volumes when a volume is
full--instead, @{b}tar@{ub} runs commands you have stored in SCRIPT-NAME.  For
example, this option can be used to eject cassettes, or to broadcast
messages such as @{b}Someone please come change my tape@{ub} when performing
unattended backups.  When SCRIPT-NAME is done, @{b}tar@{ub} will assume that the
media has been changed.

   Multi-volume archives can be modified like any other archive.  To add
files to a multi-volume archive, you need to only mount the last volume
of the archive media (and new volumes, if needed).  For all other
operations, you need to use the entire archive.

   If a multi-volume archive was labeled using @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}
(@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) (see @{"label" link "label"}) when it was created, @{b}tar@{ub} will not
automatically label volumes which are added later.  To label subsequent
volumes, specify @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) again in
conjunction with the @{b}--append@{ub} (@{b}-r@{ub}), @{b}--update@{ub} (@{b}-u@{ub}) or @{b}--concatenate@{ub}
(@{b}--catenate@{ub}, @{b}-A@{ub}) operation.

@{b}--multi-volume@{ub}
@{b}-M@{ub}
     Creates a multi-volume archive, when used in conjunction with
     @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}).  To perform any other operation on a multi-volume
     archive, specify @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) in conjunction with that
     operation.

@{b}--info-script=PROGRAM-FILE@{ub}
@{b}-F PROGRAM-FILE@{ub}
     Creates a multi-volume archive via a script.  Used in conjunction
     with @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}).

   Beware that there is @{i}no@{ui} real standard about the proper way, for a
@{b}tar@{ub} archive, to span volume boundaries.  If you have a multi-volume
created by some vendor's @{b}tar@{ub}, there is almost no chance you could read
all the volumes with GNU @{b}tar@{ub}.  The converse is also true: you may not
expect multi-volume archives created by GNU @{b}tar@{ub} to be fully recovered
by vendor's @{b}tar@{ub}.  Since there is little chance that, in mixed system
configurations, some vendor's @{b}tar@{ub} will work on another vendor's
machine, and there is a great chance that GNU @{b}tar@{ub} will work on most of
them, your best bet is to install GNU @{b}tar@{ub} on all machines between which
you know exchange of files is possible.


@endnode

@node "Tape Files" "tar.guide/Tape Files"
@prev "Multi-Volume Archives"
@toc "Using Multiple Tapes"

Tape Files
----------

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

   To give the archive a name which will be recorded in it, use the
@{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) option.  This will write a
special block identifying VOLUME-LABEL as the name of the archive to
the front of the archive which will be displayed when the archive is
listed with @{b}--list@{ub} (@{b}-t@{ub}).  If you are creating a multi-volume archive
with @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) (), then the volume label will have @{b}Volume NNN@{ub}
appended to the name you give, where NNN is the number of the volume of
the archive.  (If you use the @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub})
option when reading an archive, it checks to make sure the label on the
tape matches the one you give.  See @{"label" link "label"}.

   When @{b}tar@{ub} writes an archive to tape, it creates a single tape file.
If multiple archives are written to the same tape, one after the other,
they each get written as separate tape files.  When extracting, it is
necessary to position the tape at the right place before running @{b}tar@{ub}.
To do this, use the @{b}mt@{ub} command.  For more information on the @{b}mt@{ub} command
and on the organization of tapes into a sequence of tape files, see @{"mt" link "mt"}.

   People seem to often do:

     --label="SOME-PREFIX `date +SOME-FORMAT`"

   or such, for pushing a common date in all volumes or an archive set.


@endnode

@node "label" "tar.guide/label"
@next "verify"
@prev "Using Multiple Tapes"
@toc "Media"

Including a Label in the Archive
================================

@{i}     (This message will disappear, once this node revised.)@{ui}

@{b}-V NAME@{ub}
@{b}--label=NAME@{ub}
     Create archive with volume name NAME.

   This option causes @{b}tar@{ub} to write out a @{i}volume header@{ui} at the beginning
of the archive.  If @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) is used, each volume of the
archive will have a volume header of @{b}NAME Volume N@{ub}, where N is 1 for
the first volume, 2 for the next, and so on.

   To avoid problems caused by misplaced paper labels on the archive
media, you can include a @{i}label@{ui} entry--an archive member which contains
the name of the archive--in the archive itself.  Use the
@{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) option in conjunction with the
@{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) operation to include a label entry in the archive as it
is being created.

   If you create an archive using both @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V
ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) and @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}), each volume of the archive will
have an archive label of the form @{b}ARCHIVE-LABEL Volume N@{ub}, where N is 1
for the first volume, 2 for the next, and so on.  , for information on
creating multiple volume archives.

   If you list or extract an archive using @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V
ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}), @{b}tar@{ub} will print an error if the archive label doesn't
match the ARCHIVE-LABEL specified, and will then not list nor extract
the archive.  In those cases, ARCHIVE-LABEL argument is interpreted as
a globbing-style pattern which must match the actual magnetic volume
label.  See @{"exclude" link "exclude"}, for a precise description of how match is
attempted(1).  If the switch @{b}--multi-volume@{ub} (@{b}-M@{ub}) is being used, the
volume label matcher will also suffix ARCHIVE-LABEL by @{b} Volume [1-9]*@{ub}
if the initial match fails, before giving up.  Since the volume
numbering is automatically added in labels at creation time, it sounded
logical to equally help the user taking care of it when the archive is
being read.

   The @{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) was once called
@{b}--volume@{ub}, but is not available under that name anymore.

   To find out an archive's label entry (or to find out if an archive
has a label at all), use @{b}tar --list --verbose@{ub}.  @{b}tar@{ub} will print the
label first, and then print archive member information, as in the
example below:

     $ tar --verbose --list --file=iamanarchive
     V--------- 0 0        0 1992-03-07 12:01 iamalabel--Volume Header--
     -rw-rw-rw- ringo user 40 1990-05-21 13:30 iamafilename

@{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}
@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}
     Includes an @{i}archive-label@{ui} at the beginning of the archive when the
     archive is being created, when used in conjunction with the
     @{b}--create@{ub} (@{b}-c@{ub}) option.  Checks to make sure the archive label
     matches the one specified (when used in conjunction with the
     @{b}--extract@{ub} (@{b}--get@{ub}, @{b}-x@{ub}) option.

   To get a common information on all tapes of a series, use the
@{b}--label=ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub} (@{b}-V ARCHIVE-LABEL@{ub}) option.  For having this
information different in each series created through a single script
used on a regular basis, just manage to get some date string as part of
the label.  For example:

     $ tar cfMV /dev/tape "Daily backup for `date +%Y-%m-%d`"
     $ tar --create --file=/dev/tape --multi-volume \\
          --volume="Daily backup for `date +%Y-%m-%d`"

   Also note that each label has its own date and time, which
corresponds to when GNU @{b}tar@{ub} initially attempted to write it, often soon
after the operator launches @{b}tar@{ub} or types the carriage return telling
that the next tape is ready.  Comparing date labels does give an idea
of tape throughput only if the delays for rewinding tapes and the
operator switching them were negligible, which is ususally not the case.

   ---------- Footnotes ----------

   (1) Previous versions of @{b}tar@{ub} used full regular expression matching,
or before that, only exact string matching, instead of wildcard
matchers.  We decided for the sake of simplicity to use a uniform
matching device through @{b}tar@{ub}.


@endnode

@node "verify" "tar.guide/verify"
@next "Write Protection"
@prev "label"
@toc "Media"

Verifying Data as It is Stored
==============================

@{b}-W@{ub}
@{b}--verify@{ub}
     Attempt to verify the archive after writing.

   This option causes @{b}tar@{ub} to verify the archive after writing it.  Each
volume is checked after it is written, and any discrepancies are
recorded on the standard error output.

   Verification requires that the archive be on a back-space-able
medium.  This means pipes, some cartridge tape drives, and some other
devices cannot be verified.

   You can insure the accuracy of an archive by comparing files in the
system with archive members.  @{b}tar@{ub} can compare an archive to the file
system as the archive is being written, to verify a write operation, or
can compare a previously written archive, to insure that it is up to
date.

   To check for discrepancies in an archive immediately after it is
written, use the @{b}--verify@{ub} (@{b}-W@{ub}) option in conjunction with the @{b}--create@{ub}
(@{b}-c@{ub}) operation.  When this option is specified, @{b}tar@{ub} checks archive
members against their counterparts in the file system, and reports
discrepancies on the standard error.  In multi-volume archives, each
volume is verified after it is written, before the next volume is
written.

   To verify an archive, you must be able to read it from before the end
of the last written entry.  This option is useful for detecting data
errors on some tapes.  Archives written to pipes, some cartridge tape
drives, and some other devices cannot be verified.

   One can explicitely compare an already made archive with the file
system by using the @{b}--compare@{ub} (@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}) option, instead of using the
more automatic @{b}--verify@{ub} (@{b}-W@{ub}) option.  See @{"compare" link "compare"}.

   Note that these two options have a slightly different intent.  The
@{b}--compare@{ub} (@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}) option how identical are the logical contents of
some archive with what is on your disks, while the @{b}--verify@{ub} (@{b}-W@{ub}) option
is really for checking if the physical contents agree and if the
recording media itself is of dependable quality.  So, for the @{b}--verify@{ub}
(@{b}-W@{ub}) operation, @{b}tar@{ub} tries to defeat all in-memory cache pertaining to
the archive, while it lets the speed optimization undisturbed for the
@{b}--compare@{ub} (@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}) option.  If you nevertheless use @{b}--compare@{ub}
(@{b}--diff@{ub}, @{b}-d@{ub}) for media verification, you may have to defeat the
in-memory cache yourself, maybe by opening and reclosing the door latch
of your recording unit, forcing some doubt in your operating system
about the fact this is really the same volume as the one just written
or read.

   The @{b}--verify@{ub} (@{b}-W@{ub}) option would not be necessary if drivers were
indeed able to detect dependably all write failures.  This sometimes
require many magnetic heads, some able to read after the writes
occurred.  One would not say that drivers unable to detect all cases
are necessarily flawed, as long as programming is concerned.


@endnode

@node "Write Protection" "tar.guide/Write Protection"
@prev "verify"
@toc "Media"

Write Protection
================

   Almost all tapes and diskettes, and in a few rare cases, even disks
can be @{i}write protected@{ui}, to protect data on them from being changed.
Once an archive is written, you should write protect the media to
prevent the archive from being accidently overwritten or deleted.
(This will protect the archive from being changed with a tape or floppy
drive--it will not protect it from magnet fields or other physical
hazards).

   The write protection device itself is usually an integral part of the
physical media, and can be a two position (write enabled/write
disabled) switch, a notch which can be popped out or covered, a ring
which can be removed from the center of a tape reel, or some other
changeable feature.


@endnode

